WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.790 --> 00:00:04.720
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington DC.

00:00:22.620 --> 00:00:25.120
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: I'm conducting
an oral history on behalf

00:00:25.120 --> 00:00:28.250
of the American Folklife Center

00:00:28.250 --> 00:00:33.890
of two North Indian or
Hindustani musicians.

00:00:33.890 --> 00:00:45.170
Sarod master Soumya Chakraverty
and tabla master Debu Nayak.

00:00:45.170 --> 00:00:48.640
Previously, they played at the
Library of Congress as part

00:00:48.640 --> 00:00:50.420
of the Homegrown concert series

00:00:50.420 --> 00:00:56.210
in May during Asian-American
heritage month and [inaudible]

00:00:56.210 --> 00:01:01.350
of the American Folklife Center,
co-sponsored by the Library

00:01:01.350 --> 00:01:04.560
of Congress Asian-American
Association.

00:01:04.560 --> 00:01:07.480
And now, we'll turn
to the questions.

00:01:07.480 --> 00:01:13.400
And I'd like them to tell me a
little bit about their early life

00:01:13.400 --> 00:01:18.420
and how they got to the point
of becoming master musicians.

00:01:18.420 --> 00:01:20.180
And we'll start with you Soumya.

00:01:20.180 --> 00:01:22.060
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty:
Thank you Yasmeen.

00:01:22.060 --> 00:01:24.230
And thank you for the introduction.

00:01:24.230 --> 00:01:30.370
So, I-- And I could talk a lot
about how I got into music,

00:01:30.370 --> 00:01:35.680
but the simple answer that comes
to my mind, and I think that echoes

00:01:35.680 --> 00:01:40.730
with a lot of people of my
generation from South Asia,

00:01:40.730 --> 00:01:45.150
is they were kind of forced
into getting to music.

00:01:45.150 --> 00:01:48.850
And I used the word
forced into, because that--

00:01:48.850 --> 00:01:53.160
it seems like a coercion
technique at that point in time.

00:01:53.160 --> 00:01:58.380
But then, that coercion
unbeknownstly became a matter

00:01:58.380 --> 00:02:02.690
of love and falling in
love with the art form.

00:02:02.690 --> 00:02:07.160
Just like people are sent to
schools and, you know, apparently,

00:02:07.160 --> 00:02:09.450
I was brought into music.

00:02:09.450 --> 00:02:13.450
But for me, it's a little bit of
coercion plus also enticement.

00:02:13.450 --> 00:02:16.490
So, I come from a family

00:02:16.490 --> 00:02:21.150
where I didn't have a
musical heritage with me.

00:02:21.150 --> 00:02:24.580
But, my parents were
both interested in music.

00:02:24.580 --> 00:02:28.460
They used to attend concerts,
festivals, et cetera.

00:02:28.460 --> 00:02:30.840
And I have two siblings,
both older than me,

00:02:30.840 --> 00:02:34.940
and also had other extended
family members living with us.

00:02:34.940 --> 00:02:39.270
And everybody was doing some
sort of music, playing some sort

00:02:39.270 --> 00:02:41.760
of instrument or the other.

00:02:41.760 --> 00:02:45.250
And mostly, it was
string instruments

00:02:45.250 --> 00:02:49.060
like violin, sitar, sarod, vocal.

00:02:49.060 --> 00:02:52.360
And they were missing
a tabla player.

00:02:52.360 --> 00:02:58.750
So, I sat-- And I was
enticed by the concept

00:02:58.750 --> 00:03:03.380
of rhythm having heard live
concerts and as well as recordings.

00:03:03.380 --> 00:03:09.160
So, I started jumping in and
started keeping the beat.

00:03:09.160 --> 00:03:10.460
And how would I keep the beat,

00:03:10.460 --> 00:03:12.680
because I didn't have
tablas with me.

00:03:12.680 --> 00:03:20.070
So, I had two metal containers
of cereal boxes and baby food.

00:03:20.070 --> 00:03:22.980
So, those are my--
the dayan and bayan.

00:03:22.980 --> 00:03:24.630
And I use to sit and
play tabla with them.

00:03:24.630 --> 00:03:27.690
So, that was my initiation
into music.

00:03:27.690 --> 00:03:30.770
Seeing my level of
interest, my parents decided

00:03:30.770 --> 00:03:32.990
that maybe I should have a tabla.

00:03:32.990 --> 00:03:39.220
And so, I was-- I started learning
tabla at the age of eight, I think.

00:03:39.220 --> 00:03:43.200 position:56%
And also have a brief stint learning
western violin at school because,

00:03:43.200 --> 00:03:46.340
you know, I thought it was cool
to, you know, go to chapel.

00:03:46.340 --> 00:03:51.560
I actually studied in a Episcopal
Methodist school in India.

00:03:51.560 --> 00:03:55.300 position:56%
And we had chapel service every
Monday and there was music along it.

00:03:55.300 --> 00:03:59.380 position:56%
So, I was very interested in the
chorale singing and the violin play.

00:03:59.380 --> 00:04:04.650 position:56%
So, my exploration into western
music also started at the same time.

00:04:04.650 --> 00:04:10.990
And I learned tabla for
about a year and a half.

00:04:10.990 --> 00:04:14.050
And, I can't say if I was very
good at it, but the concept

00:04:14.050 --> 00:04:16.820
of rhythm came to my mind.

00:04:16.820 --> 00:04:21.940
And, around 11, I actually
switched over to the sarod.

00:04:21.940 --> 00:04:23.240
How that happened?

00:04:23.240 --> 00:04:24.540
I don't, again, know.

00:04:24.540 --> 00:04:26.230
That may have been
an act of coercion.

00:04:26.230 --> 00:04:31.700
It's been so many years, I
can't quite remember vividly.

00:04:31.700 --> 00:04:35.310
But, it took me a little bit of
time switching from the tabla

00:04:35.310 --> 00:04:37.040
to the-- to a string instrument.

00:04:37.040 --> 00:04:41.180
But when it did happened
over a course of maybe three,

00:04:41.180 --> 00:04:45.730
four years of just readapting
to learning another instrument.

00:04:45.730 --> 00:04:47.660
And because of playing the sarod,

00:04:47.660 --> 00:04:52.750
and I'll say why a little bit
later during the interview,

00:04:52.750 --> 00:04:55.170
I had to give up on the
tabla and the violin.

00:04:55.170 --> 00:05:00.230
Because I, you know,
[inaudible] to go play the sarod.

00:05:00.230 --> 00:05:05.890
But, so, ultimately, the tabla
and the violin both diminished

00:05:05.890 --> 00:05:07.830
and sarod became my
primary instrument.

00:05:07.830 --> 00:05:12.790
So, that, in short, is my journey.

00:05:12.790 --> 00:05:16.720
And how the journey began
almost, I would say,

00:05:16.720 --> 00:05:21.210 position:56%
37 years ago and it still continues.

00:05:21.210 --> 00:05:22.510
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: That's great.

00:05:22.510 --> 00:05:26.710
And how-- What's it about the
sarod that really attracted you?

00:05:26.710 --> 00:05:31.520
I mean, what made you give up
the other two and choose this?

00:05:31.520 --> 00:05:34.980
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Again, at
that point, when you're a boy of 10

00:05:34.980 --> 00:05:38.510
or 11 years old, you just do
what your parents tell you.

00:05:38.510 --> 00:05:39.810
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: OK.

00:05:39.810 --> 00:05:41.130
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: And,
one day it's like, hey,

00:05:41.130 --> 00:05:43.840
you know, you learn sarod.

00:05:43.840 --> 00:05:50.050
And then, the other day it is the--
or maybe you start with the tabla,

00:05:50.050 --> 00:05:51.960
and then you learn the sarod.

00:05:51.960 --> 00:05:55.210
But that being said,
there were certain aspects

00:05:55.210 --> 00:05:58.610 position:56%
of the instrument that attracted me.

00:05:58.610 --> 00:06:03.130
I think the sarod and the sitar
are probably the most common string

00:06:03.130 --> 00:06:06.750
instruments in India, or
at least in Northern India.

00:06:06.750 --> 00:06:13.770
And I always felt that there was
a-- the gender gap between the--

00:06:13.770 --> 00:06:17.690
those two instruments, the sarod
with its very deep sound kind

00:06:17.690 --> 00:06:21.280
of sounded like a male, very
macho kind of an instrument.

00:06:21.280 --> 00:06:25.640
And what-- the ability to do a
lot of fast runs and, you know,

00:06:25.640 --> 00:06:30.020
the patterns like the
tabla was very masculine.

00:06:30.020 --> 00:06:34.040
On the other hand, I heard
the sitar beautiful as it is,

00:06:34.040 --> 00:06:39.280
I just felt more bias
towards the sarod.

00:06:39.280 --> 00:06:41.990
And that may have, you know,

00:06:41.990 --> 00:06:45.280
propelled me in that direction
plus some gentle cajoling

00:06:45.280 --> 00:06:46.660
from my parents.

00:06:46.660 --> 00:06:47.960
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: OK.

00:06:47.960 --> 00:06:49.260
Always helps.

00:06:49.260 --> 00:06:51.430
And you Devapriya?

00:06:51.430 --> 00:06:54.150
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak:
Where do I start?

00:06:54.150 --> 00:06:59.300
My mom says that I started
playing when I was two

00:06:59.300 --> 00:07:01.580
and a half, three years old.

00:07:01.580 --> 00:07:04.720
So, I did purposely
asked her this question,

00:07:04.720 --> 00:07:07.080
but when did you noticed me play?

00:07:07.080 --> 00:07:09.130
She said that, you
know, when you're two,

00:07:09.130 --> 00:07:12.110
two and a half you've
been always hitting

00:07:12.110 --> 00:07:14.290 position:56%
against one thing against the other.

00:07:14.290 --> 00:07:19.410
And then, anything you get
you just start drumming on it.

00:07:19.410 --> 00:07:25.320
So, those days, it used to
be sort of like customary

00:07:25.320 --> 00:07:30.580
that when the summer vacation
comes-- I grew up in Kolkata.

00:07:30.580 --> 00:07:34.200
And my parents-- my father,

00:07:34.200 --> 00:07:38.580
was in the West Bengal
Civil Service in Bengal.

00:07:38.580 --> 00:07:43.580
And so, when the summer time
comes, the holiday will start

00:07:43.580 --> 00:07:46.260 position:56%
and we will go to my ancestral home,

00:07:46.260 --> 00:07:51.350
which is 76 to 80 kilometers
from Kolkata.

00:07:51.350 --> 00:07:56.730
It's a place called Punjab gharana
and it's a small principality,

00:07:56.730 --> 00:08:03.760
where my grandfather and
his ancestry came from there

00:08:03.760 --> 00:08:06.160
and it's nothing but music.

00:08:06.160 --> 00:08:07.460
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Really.

00:08:07.460 --> 00:08:10.330
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: So, my
mom came from this family

00:08:10.330 --> 00:08:16.600
and as she put it many times
that music to me is in my blood.

00:08:16.600 --> 00:08:23.660
So but, I don't know how this
particular instrument got ingrained

00:08:23.660 --> 00:08:27.610
or I got sort of like,
drawn towards it.

00:08:27.610 --> 00:08:32.390
And then there are so many other
instruments which I was exposed to.

00:08:32.390 --> 00:08:38.350
My mother, she is a fantastic
sitar player when she was young.

00:08:38.350 --> 00:08:44.520
And, she played until, you
know, she was in her late 60's.

00:08:44.520 --> 00:08:48.820
But, coming back to when we used
to visit the ancestral home,

00:08:48.820 --> 00:08:50.660
I used to see my grandfather
practice,

00:08:50.660 --> 00:08:59.600
his brothers are practicing, either
sitar, vocal, surbahar, jaltarang,

00:08:59.600 --> 00:09:02.420
tablas, pakhavaj and flute.

00:09:02.420 --> 00:09:06.680
So, all these instruments were
being, you know, I was exposed to.

00:09:06.680 --> 00:09:12.050
And, I have seen my grandfather
was teaching three things.

00:09:12.050 --> 00:09:17.190
One, he used to first start the
morning with the vocal, and then,

00:09:17.190 --> 00:09:20.090
as he's playing vocal
he would play tabla,

00:09:20.090 --> 00:09:22.800
but I was always drawn
towards tabla.

00:09:22.800 --> 00:09:26.190
So, he saw this interest
in me and he said--

00:09:26.190 --> 00:09:30.770
and while he was playing and
singing, other students gathered

00:09:30.770 --> 00:09:33.700
around him, and they
were all just singing.

00:09:33.700 --> 00:09:39.290
And some of them are either doing
it on their leg or they're doing it

00:09:39.290 --> 00:09:42.630
like this or they're
just doing this.

00:09:42.630 --> 00:09:43.930
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Right.

00:09:43.930 --> 00:09:46.110
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak:
Just to keep the beat.

00:09:46.110 --> 00:09:50.710
I got-- I don't know how, but
I somehow got drawn into this.

00:09:50.710 --> 00:09:55.090
And sooner or later, I
can't put my finger on it.

00:09:55.090 --> 00:09:57.730
But sooner or later,
a set of drums came

00:09:57.730 --> 00:10:00.130
into the picture and
I started playing.

00:10:00.130 --> 00:10:02.840
So nobody really taught me, "OK,

00:10:02.840 --> 00:10:05.200
this is what you do to
play-- do this sound.

00:10:05.200 --> 00:10:10.890
Or this is what you do to do
this sound, or this sound."

00:10:10.890 --> 00:10:14.310
It was just-- I mean,
naturally came to me.

00:10:14.310 --> 00:10:18.860
So before you know it, I was
already playing with them.

00:10:18.860 --> 00:10:22.900
And this continued for years.

00:10:22.900 --> 00:10:24.760
I don't know when it stopped.

00:10:24.760 --> 00:10:26.740
But eventually, they
saw the interest

00:10:26.740 --> 00:10:30.190
in me, my-- both my parents.

00:10:30.190 --> 00:10:36.560
More-- so my-- From my mother side
and then, my father was very busy.

00:10:36.560 --> 00:10:43.980 position:56%
So she, at some point, when we moved
to Kolkata from one summer vacation,

00:10:43.980 --> 00:10:50.760
she introduced me to a maestro
who was teaching close to my home.

00:10:50.760 --> 00:10:53.860
His name is Radhakanta Nandi.

00:10:53.860 --> 00:10:59.250
And he was coming close
to my home to teach.

00:10:59.250 --> 00:11:07.700
And I got into that class and,
you know, we started learning

00:11:07.700 --> 00:11:09.730
and there-- so, there are a lot

00:11:09.730 --> 00:11:12.820
of neighborhood kids
too learning tabla.

00:11:12.820 --> 00:11:16.360
But I somehow started excelling
in tabla and I would play

00:11:16.360 --> 00:11:17.770
with different instruments.

00:11:17.770 --> 00:11:22.110
Probably, because I was playing
in my ancestral home and bringing

00:11:22.110 --> 00:11:26.200
that knowledge, playing with other
instruments as well as vocal,

00:11:26.200 --> 00:11:31.610
as well as, you know, the
intricacies that goes with it,

00:11:31.610 --> 00:11:36.050
I'll bring all of that
and then put in practice.

00:11:36.050 --> 00:11:38.370
So that's pretty much
how it happened.

00:11:38.370 --> 00:11:47.070
And, you know, eventually I've--
as I aged, slowly, slowly,

00:11:47.070 --> 00:11:51.450
I was exposed to different
conferences, concerts and so on.

00:11:51.450 --> 00:11:56.340
So, that also has a lot of,
you know, influence on me.

00:11:56.340 --> 00:12:00.760
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Do you continue--
How does that work into music?

00:12:00.760 --> 00:12:07.730
Do you follow the school
of your first tabla teacher

00:12:07.730 --> 00:12:12.610
or how do you decide what
style your tabla play or is--

00:12:12.610 --> 00:12:17.110
I mean, when you talk about your
musical pedigree, how do you--

00:12:17.110 --> 00:12:18.410
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yeah.

00:12:18.410 --> 00:12:19.710
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: -- how
do you talk about that?

00:12:19.710 --> 00:12:21.010
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yeah.

00:12:21.010 --> 00:12:25.830
When you're learning it initially,
you don't worry about any of that.

00:12:25.830 --> 00:12:28.620
You just blindly follow
your teacher, OK,

00:12:28.620 --> 00:12:32.320
whatever the teacher
is singing or playing.

00:12:32.320 --> 00:12:35.130
We learned two things
simultaneously,

00:12:35.130 --> 00:12:38.950
the vocal part and the rhythm part.

00:12:38.950 --> 00:12:44.180
So, how does-- in may case at
least, how does, with a song

00:12:44.180 --> 00:12:51.560
or how does with-- how does rhythm
fit into a vocal piece so to speak.

00:12:51.560 --> 00:12:52.860
We call it Bandish.

00:12:52.860 --> 00:12:54.160
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Yeah.

00:12:54.160 --> 00:12:56.590
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: In a Bandish,
how does the vocal part goes?

00:12:56.590 --> 00:12:59.120
What is the rhythmic pattern in it?

00:12:59.120 --> 00:13:03.450
What is the-- they call it-- in
the tabla term, it's called theka.

00:13:03.450 --> 00:13:07.950
How does the theka takes
shape in a Bandish?

00:13:07.950 --> 00:13:10.050
So, that's how I learned.

00:13:10.050 --> 00:13:15.900
Now, coming back to the question
of schooling, I mean, later on,

00:13:15.900 --> 00:13:20.630
I came to know that there
are six schools in tabla.

00:13:20.630 --> 00:13:26.510
But the school that I was learning
with my grandfather was Punjab.

00:13:26.510 --> 00:13:27.810
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Yeah.

00:13:27.810 --> 00:13:29.110
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: The school
that I came to learn later

00:13:29.110 --> 00:13:33.250
on in Kolkata was Benares.

00:13:33.250 --> 00:13:38.940
So, I did not notice the
style-- stylistic difference,

00:13:38.940 --> 00:13:44.460
except when certain syllables,
much later I realized it,

00:13:44.460 --> 00:13:48.910
that there are some
differences in finger techniques.

00:13:48.910 --> 00:13:52.920
And we-- Initially,
when we're learning

00:13:52.920 --> 00:13:56.690
in my ancestral home following it
blindly, when I came to Kolkata

00:13:56.690 --> 00:14:00.540
after the holidays, we
will follow that blindly.

00:14:00.540 --> 00:14:07.980
So somehow, a style of my own got
created and I just ran with it.

00:14:07.980 --> 00:14:09.280
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Right.

00:14:09.280 --> 00:14:10.580
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yeah.

00:14:10.580 --> 00:14:11.880
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: And what--

00:14:11.880 --> 00:14:15.250
How would you answer that
question about, you know,

00:14:15.250 --> 00:14:20.110
your musical lineage
in terms of style?

00:14:20.110 --> 00:14:21.410
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Yeah.

00:14:21.410 --> 00:14:22.710
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: And
how you, you know,

00:14:22.710 --> 00:14:24.700
at this point, get to this point?

00:14:24.700 --> 00:14:28.320
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: So, I--
My creating has differed slightly

00:14:28.320 --> 00:14:31.790
from Debu's that because
I pretty much learned

00:14:31.790 --> 00:14:35.840
from one person belonging
to one school.

00:14:35.840 --> 00:14:41.560
We also have at least three
different musical lineages

00:14:41.560 --> 00:14:44.180
for sarod, our schools.

00:14:44.180 --> 00:14:50.230
But because my training, even
to this day that if I've picked

00:14:50.230 --> 00:14:56.940
up nuances, it has stayed
within our school of--

00:14:56.940 --> 00:15:00.640
and our school comes
from a small village

00:15:00.640 --> 00:15:03.040
in northern India called
Shahjahanpur,

00:15:03.040 --> 00:15:05.830
named after the Emperor Shah Jahan.

00:15:05.830 --> 00:15:11.420
And the Shahjahanpur technique
is very different from some

00:15:11.420 --> 00:15:18.160 position:56%
of the other techniques, one being
Gwalior, again, named after a place,

00:15:18.160 --> 00:15:22.240
which the famous maestro of
Sarod, Amjad Ali Khan belongs to.

00:15:22.240 --> 00:15:27.700
And also, Maihar, which was a
much later school but founded

00:15:27.700 --> 00:15:33.690
by the father of, again, the
legendary Ustad Allaudin Khan.

00:15:33.690 --> 00:15:38.410
So, these schools have different
playing techniques, but--

00:15:38.410 --> 00:15:43.560
and I've heard them and
like he said, as we grow up,

00:15:43.560 --> 00:15:47.920
when you are learning you just
follow what is taught to you,

00:15:47.920 --> 00:15:51.480
but as you grow up and as you
listen to different forms of music

00:15:51.480 --> 00:15:52.810
and different playing techniques,

00:15:52.810 --> 00:15:55.810
you start to discern
those differences

00:15:55.810 --> 00:16:01.690
and either you can invite
them or you can choose

00:16:01.690 --> 00:16:06.450
to retain your own specific flavor.

00:16:06.450 --> 00:16:11.890
I think, with the advent
of electronic music,

00:16:11.890 --> 00:16:16.380
what has happened is the knowledge
sharing has become more profound.

00:16:16.380 --> 00:16:21.610
It used to be pretty much, you
know, based on the formal training

00:16:21.610 --> 00:16:25.960
that one has from a teacher, and
say, if I learn a composition

