00:18:10.680 --> 00:18:15.370
So now, it would be nice to
sort of segue into having each

00:18:15.370 --> 00:18:18.840
of you talk a little bit about
your instruments and sort

00:18:18.840 --> 00:18:25.850
of situate them in, you know,
the history of this particular--

00:18:25.850 --> 00:18:30.670
and how it-- musical instrument
and how it is changing.

00:18:30.670 --> 00:18:35.420
If it's changing or if you adapt
it on an individual level if it,

00:18:35.420 --> 00:18:40.250
you know, how versatile these
are to change and in adaptation.

00:18:40.250 --> 00:18:41.550
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: So,

00:18:41.550 --> 00:18:47.980
the history of the sarod probably
goes back about 200 to 300 years.

00:18:47.980 --> 00:18:52.310
You know, when you consider how old
Indian music is, it doesn't seem

00:18:52.310 --> 00:18:57.440
that old, probably just, you
know, somewhere on the middle

00:18:57.440 --> 00:19:03.230
of the British era in India that
the sarod formally took its place.

00:19:03.230 --> 00:19:08.120
And there are many theories of
how the instrument came to being.

00:19:08.120 --> 00:19:12.160
Some said it was adapted from
other Indian instruments,

00:19:12.160 --> 00:19:16.710
some say it has its roots
in Persia and Afghanistan

00:19:16.710 --> 00:19:18.630
and even, you know, Middle East.

00:19:18.630 --> 00:19:21.390
And the fact is that, I think,

00:19:21.390 --> 00:19:24.240
everybody is true to
a certain extent.

00:19:24.240 --> 00:19:26.780
There are certain aspects
of the instrument

00:19:26.780 --> 00:19:30.720
that when you hear the instrument
or you look at its shape,

00:19:30.720 --> 00:19:33.910
you find similarities with
other string instruments

00:19:33.910 --> 00:19:36.120
like the tar, the rubab, the oud--

00:19:36.120 --> 00:19:40.090
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Could you be
specific about that in terms of--

00:19:40.090 --> 00:19:41.390
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Yeah.

00:19:41.390 --> 00:19:45.380 position:56%
In terms of the fact that there's a
hollow air chamber, that there's a--

00:19:45.380 --> 00:19:48.980
you know, ultimately
at the end of the day,

00:19:48.980 --> 00:19:55.060
any kind of plucked instrument is
a piece of string or some pieces

00:19:55.060 --> 00:20:00.040
of string that are one
between two knotted areas.

00:20:00.040 --> 00:20:04.630
So, you've got a peg, you've
got a, you know, eye here.

00:20:04.630 --> 00:20:11.110
But most of these instruments, the
tar, the rubab have a similar type

00:20:11.110 --> 00:20:15.600 position:56%
of shape, a very rounded or somewhat
elliptical, in certain cases,

00:20:15.600 --> 00:20:18.240
a drum which has an air chamber

00:20:18.240 --> 00:20:21.920
that amplifies the music
and then a finger plate.

00:20:21.920 --> 00:20:25.630
And they tend to be
fretless instruments.

00:20:25.630 --> 00:20:30.240
The instruments that were
traditionally developed

00:20:30.240 --> 00:20:32.350
in India were fretted instrument.

00:20:32.350 --> 00:20:38.740
Most notably was the a
whole family of veenas.

00:20:38.740 --> 00:20:45.680
The veena is a instrument that's
made from two large pieces of gourd

00:20:45.680 --> 00:20:50.550
which grows abundantly in India
and that's attached to a bamboo

00:20:50.550 --> 00:20:55.100
or wooden finger board and
they have frets in between

00:20:55.100 --> 00:21:00.910
and with the strings tightened
on both sides or by pegs.

00:21:00.910 --> 00:21:04.190
Now, because of these two
large gourds, it's kind of held

00:21:04.190 --> 00:21:06.900
in an upright position and played.

00:21:06.900 --> 00:21:10.650
Now, there are obviously,
variances of these

00:21:10.650 --> 00:21:13.380
but the veena produces
a very deep sound

00:21:13.380 --> 00:21:16.470
that is amplified by the gourds.

00:21:16.470 --> 00:21:23.180
When there were some Afghan
musicians who were the rubabias,

00:21:23.180 --> 00:21:26.000
the rubab players,
they came to India.

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:30.200
The rubab, if you look at a picture
of it and I wish I had a photo

00:21:30.200 --> 00:21:34.850
to show you, it is actually
almost like a miniature version

00:21:34.850 --> 00:21:37.150
of the sarod, looks very similar.

00:21:37.150 --> 00:21:40.840
The only difference is the drum
is elliptical and doesn't have

00:21:40.840 --> 00:21:43.240
as many strings, does
have a few strings

00:21:43.240 --> 00:21:46.470
and the strings are made
of either gut or silk.

00:21:46.470 --> 00:21:52.560 position:56%
And the-- Because the air chamber is
much shallow and also much smaller,

00:21:52.560 --> 00:21:59.450
the instrument have a very
dull, kind of a blunt sound.

00:21:59.450 --> 00:22:03.490
But I would also say it's a
little bit more earthy in nature.

00:22:03.490 --> 00:22:05.870
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Wasn't it
also an accompany on a--

00:22:05.870 --> 00:22:07.170
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: It is.

00:22:07.170 --> 00:22:08.470
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: -- a
vocal accompaniment?

00:22:08.470 --> 00:22:10.270
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: It is
a vocal accompaniment mainly

00:22:10.270 --> 00:22:11.700
as a folk instrument.

00:22:11.700 --> 00:22:13.000
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Right.

00:22:13.000 --> 00:22:15.810 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: And because
of there was not a lot of sustenance

00:22:15.810 --> 00:22:20.460
in the note, it had this
kind of dull clangy sound.

00:22:20.460 --> 00:22:26.220
It was used to-- as almost like to
keep the beat and in some cases,

00:22:26.220 --> 00:22:30.730
acted like a percussion, although
not a percussion instrument.

00:22:30.730 --> 00:22:33.310
So, if you listen to a lot
of Middle Eastern music,

00:22:33.310 --> 00:22:36.620
you'll hear their rubab being
extensively played even today.

00:22:36.620 --> 00:22:39.410
So, these were the
rubabias that were like--

00:22:39.410 --> 00:22:43.460
they were marching band
instrumentalists that came to India

00:22:43.460 --> 00:22:45.840
and they settled down
somewhere in northern India.

00:22:45.840 --> 00:22:47.580
And they heard cork musicians

00:22:47.580 --> 00:22:52.390
in northern India playing the
veena and also local music.

00:22:52.390 --> 00:22:58.070
And they got this idea of
experimenting with the instrument

00:22:58.070 --> 00:23:05.160
to make it sound more like a voice
and to have build more sustenance.

00:23:05.160 --> 00:23:08.710
So in order to do so,
they start to experiment,

00:23:08.710 --> 00:23:11.180 position:56%
make it a slightly bigger instrument

00:23:11.180 --> 00:23:16.060
with the expansion
of the air chamber.

00:23:16.060 --> 00:23:21.920
So, you can see this camel hump, as
we call it, to expand this in a way

00:23:21.920 --> 00:23:26.410
that it hollows out and
connects with the broader drum.

00:23:26.410 --> 00:23:29.670
Now, what that does, it
creates more resonance

00:23:29.670 --> 00:23:34.860
and also the strings got replaced
with the advent of metal strings

00:23:34.860 --> 00:23:38.440
when the metal drawing techniques
and metal strings being available

00:23:38.440 --> 00:23:40.890 position:56%
for piano and for other instruments.

00:23:40.890 --> 00:23:44.130
Metal strings became
popular somewhere, I think,

00:23:44.130 --> 00:23:48.760
I'm thinking 18th century and
even maybe later at 19th century,

00:23:48.760 --> 00:23:53.470
and they started to use them on the
sarod as well as other instruments.

00:23:53.470 --> 00:24:01.110
Now-- And the cover on the
drum, it's a sheep-skin color.

00:24:01.110 --> 00:24:02.410
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Yeah.

00:24:02.410 --> 00:24:04.130
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty:
Because the size

00:24:04.130 --> 00:24:07.260
of the air chamber being increased

00:24:07.260 --> 00:24:11.940
and also another additional
air chamber-- this is all--

00:24:11.940 --> 00:24:16.260 position:56%
serves both as the rest as well as
a kind of an additional air chamber.

00:24:16.260 --> 00:24:18.500
The sound of the sustenance

00:24:18.500 --> 00:24:22.070
of the string [music]
increased significantly.

00:24:22.070 --> 00:24:26.220
And that allowed a lot of
melodic work to be performed

00:24:26.220 --> 00:24:30.500
which we could not do
if you played in a--

00:24:30.500 --> 00:24:34.420
with an instrument that didn't
have as much sustenance.

00:24:34.420 --> 00:24:36.510
So, what started to happen--

00:24:36.510 --> 00:24:39.680
and then, the addition
of these little strings

00:24:39.680 --> 00:24:43.320
that go underneath the
bridge, the main bridge,

00:24:43.320 --> 00:24:47.000
which are called the sympathetic
strings and they are for resonance.

00:24:47.000 --> 00:24:51.150
They're not actually plucked but
when you play a note by, you know,

00:24:51.150 --> 00:24:54.650
this-- being in the same
frequency, it starts to vibrate.

00:24:54.650 --> 00:24:57.590
And by the vibration it
accentuates the melody.

00:24:57.590 --> 00:25:00.690
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: And were those
adopted from sitar or veena?

00:25:00.690 --> 00:25:04.600
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: They were
used in the veena, the surbahar

00:25:04.600 --> 00:25:10.230
and also some of the other
types of rubabs that existed.

00:25:10.230 --> 00:25:15.340
The precursor to the sarod
was another instrument called

00:25:15.340 --> 00:25:16.810
the sursringar.

00:25:16.810 --> 00:25:23.070
And if you look at it today, it
still is played in some provinces

00:25:23.070 --> 00:25:27.940
in northern India, mainly the
Sikh religion, they use it.

00:25:27.940 --> 00:25:32.820
The rubab and the sursringar are
used for Sikh religious chanting

00:25:32.820 --> 00:25:35.840
and they have sympathetic
strings, and they--

00:25:35.840 --> 00:25:40.840
that's where the sarodias
or the rubabias originally,

00:25:40.840 --> 00:25:42.760
they started to get this idea.

00:25:42.760 --> 00:25:45.870
So, after a few rounds
of metamorphosis,

00:25:45.870 --> 00:25:50.490
they created an instrument, which
is very different by the way

00:25:50.490 --> 00:25:54.850
from the sarod that you see today.

00:25:54.850 --> 00:26:02.900
And the-- So, initial sarods had a
very elliptical drum and the depth

00:26:02.900 --> 00:26:04.770
of the air chamber was not as much.

00:26:04.770 --> 00:26:10.210
But over course of time,
with more experimentation,

00:26:10.210 --> 00:26:14.670
there was more resonance
added to it.

00:26:14.670 --> 00:26:17.470
And it continue-- To
answer your question,

00:26:17.470 --> 00:26:19.390
yes, it continues to evolve.

00:26:19.390 --> 00:26:22.550
There have been many
different variations added,

00:26:22.550 --> 00:26:27.850
like this rounded drum finally
came through the Maihar gharana.

00:26:27.850 --> 00:26:30.840
Although, I belong to
the Shahjahanpur gharana,

00:26:30.840 --> 00:26:37.830
I play this round drum instrument,
which is an experimentation

00:26:37.830 --> 00:26:40.080
that was [inaudible] and
made this drum more round,

00:26:40.080 --> 00:26:44.020
thereby having a more
rounded and deep sound.

00:26:44.020 --> 00:26:48.350
And, you know, these days with
the advent of electronic music,

00:26:48.350 --> 00:26:50.900
there's also, you know,
experimentation going

00:26:50.900 --> 00:26:56.770
on with making electronic
versions of the sarod, which again,

00:26:56.770 --> 00:26:58.550
I would call out back
if there's difference

00:26:58.550 --> 00:27:00.730
between an acoustic guitar
and a classical guitar.

00:27:00.730 --> 00:27:03.310
Their sound is very different
instruments, they are both guitars

00:27:03.310 --> 00:27:05.470
but they are very different
instruments.

00:27:05.470 --> 00:27:07.820
And likewise, the electric sarod

00:27:07.820 --> 00:27:12.940
and the regular classical sarod
are very different instruments.

00:27:12.940 --> 00:27:17.570
So, that's a bit about my--
well this instrument, obviously,

00:27:17.570 --> 00:27:20.760
there's a lot of technical
details I can go into.

00:27:20.760 --> 00:27:23.690
But I'll see if you have
