00:27:28.400 --> 00:27:29.700
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: OK.

00:27:29.700 --> 00:27:35.950
So regarding tabla, tabla is
relatively in the annals of history

00:27:35.950 --> 00:27:39.500
with other Indian percussive
instruments,

00:27:39.500 --> 00:27:42.520
a relatively young instrument.

00:27:42.520 --> 00:27:48.380
It happened-- In other words,
a tabla came to India as part

00:27:48.380 --> 00:27:53.790
of probably the Muslim
invasion that took place

00:27:53.790 --> 00:27:57.450 position:56%
in many times in the Indian history.

00:27:57.450 --> 00:28:04.650 position:56%
But it came around-- and there are
again, different school of thoughts,

00:28:04.650 --> 00:28:09.310
it came around between
13th and 14th century.

00:28:09.310 --> 00:28:15.950
And during these invasions
from Persia to India,

00:28:15.950 --> 00:28:20.970
a lot of learned men and
philosophers and musicians,

00:28:20.970 --> 00:28:27.660
they also came and they remained in
India, never went back with them.

00:28:27.660 --> 00:28:34.690
One of these, I call
it saint or musicians

00:28:34.690 --> 00:28:36.330
so to speak was Amir Khusrow.

00:28:36.330 --> 00:28:37.630
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: All right.

00:28:37.630 --> 00:28:38.930
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty:
And he was a poet also.

00:28:38.930 --> 00:28:40.230
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak:
And he was a poet also.

00:28:40.230 --> 00:28:41.530
And he wrote many--

00:28:41.530 --> 00:28:42.830
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Many music, yeah.

00:28:42.830 --> 00:28:44.130
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: -- many--

00:28:44.130 --> 00:28:45.430
he created many musical
instruments as well.

00:28:45.430 --> 00:28:46.730
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: OK.

00:28:46.730 --> 00:28:48.030
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak:
So, and there are--

00:28:48.030 --> 00:28:49.330
Anyway, there are different
school of thoughts

00:28:49.330 --> 00:28:52.550
about Amir Khusrow being
the creator of tabla or not.

00:28:52.550 --> 00:28:57.490 position:56%
So, Amir Khusrow, one thing
they're, you know, and they do agree

00:28:57.490 --> 00:29:04.820
on that here is a guy who came from
Persia and studied Indian music.

00:29:04.820 --> 00:29:06.770
And how did he do that?

00:29:06.770 --> 00:29:09.990
By going to different places.

00:29:09.990 --> 00:29:15.080
And one of the areas that he
went was he used to listen

00:29:15.080 --> 00:29:17.700
to the Hindu chants in the temples.

00:29:17.700 --> 00:29:20.740
And with the chants came a lot

00:29:20.740 --> 00:29:25.050
of the musical chants
that he used to observe.

00:29:25.050 --> 00:29:27.860
And he used to observe,
not only the chants,

00:29:27.860 --> 00:29:33.440
the way the melodic
structure was coming through,

00:29:33.440 --> 00:29:37.390
he also used to observe the musical
instruments that are being played

00:29:37.390 --> 00:29:43.060
with these melodies and chants.

00:29:43.060 --> 00:29:45.830
One such instrument
is called pakhawaj.

00:29:45.830 --> 00:29:47.130
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Yes.

00:29:47.130 --> 00:29:48.440
I heard this apocryphal
story of that.

00:29:48.440 --> 00:29:49.740
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yes.

00:29:49.740 --> 00:29:52.960
And pakhawaj is known
as the mother of tabla.

00:29:52.960 --> 00:29:54.260
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Right.

00:29:54.260 --> 00:29:55.560
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Why?

00:29:55.560 --> 00:29:59.000
Because pakhawaj used to be
part of the particular type

00:29:59.000 --> 00:30:02.040
of genre called dhrupad sangeet.

00:30:02.040 --> 00:30:06.270
And dhrupad used to be called
the original classical form

00:30:06.270 --> 00:30:07.570
of vocal music.

00:30:07.570 --> 00:30:10.370
And pakhawaj used to
be played, still does,

00:30:10.370 --> 00:30:12.700
and the people play
pakhawaj with it.

00:30:12.700 --> 00:30:16.310
But Amir Khusrow looked
at that instrument

00:30:16.310 --> 00:30:18.220
and he had a different idea.

00:30:18.220 --> 00:30:19.520
He thought that--

00:30:19.520 --> 00:30:20.920
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Maybe you
should describe what the pakhawaj

00:30:20.920 --> 00:30:22.220
looks like.

00:30:22.220 --> 00:30:23.520
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Yeah,
what it looks like?

00:30:23.520 --> 00:30:24.820
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Well,

00:30:24.820 --> 00:30:26.120
the pakhawaj is a cylindrical
instrument, OK.

00:30:26.120 --> 00:30:29.130
So, if I put it bluntly,
it will look like this.

00:30:29.130 --> 00:30:34.380
So, if you put it sidewise, it
will have a bigger head to play it

00:30:34.380 --> 00:30:39.090
like this in a sidewise
way and played like this.

00:30:39.090 --> 00:30:40.390
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: And
it's played with a slap.

00:30:40.390 --> 00:30:42.520
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: And
the slap, et cetera.

00:30:42.520 --> 00:30:45.480
But, you know, I will come
to that when I will explain

00:30:45.480 --> 00:30:49.980
to you the way the
finger techniques evolved.

00:30:49.980 --> 00:30:53.960
So, what happened was--
his idea was,

00:30:53.960 --> 00:30:57.010
this instrument could
be played better

00:30:57.010 --> 00:31:00.520
if we sit in an upright position.

00:31:00.520 --> 00:31:02.480
Now, the geographical location

00:31:02.480 --> 00:31:05.630
of Amir Khusrow at
this point was Delhi.

00:31:05.630 --> 00:31:09.660
And because he came up with
this instrument in Delhi,

00:31:09.660 --> 00:31:11.760
the Delhi gharana started.

00:31:11.760 --> 00:31:15.770
So, Delhi school of tabla
playing started and the first guy

00:31:15.770 --> 00:31:20.080
in recorded history that we know
of, his name is Siddhar Khan.

00:31:20.080 --> 00:31:25.100
And Siddhar Khan belong to
Delhi and he was living close

00:31:25.100 --> 00:31:30.010
to where Amir Khusrow's dargah
was, where he used to live.

00:31:30.010 --> 00:31:37.000
And Siddhar Khan picked it up and
he started playing it and sooner

00:31:37.000 --> 00:31:40.370
or later, a school was formed.

00:31:40.370 --> 00:31:42.310
Delhi gharana started.

00:31:42.310 --> 00:31:48.430
And as he was, you know, as the
school was getting older and older,

00:31:48.430 --> 00:31:53.580
different students came to learn
from him and then they would learn

00:31:53.580 --> 00:31:56.020
from him and they would
find their own way

00:31:56.020 --> 00:31:59.390
to tweak the instrument and so on.

00:31:59.390 --> 00:32:03.200
Speaking of the instrument
itself, the first instrument

00:32:03.200 --> 00:32:09.190
in recorded history as I know it
is made of wood as pakhawaj was.

00:32:09.190 --> 00:32:12.660
He just cuts it into half,
put it in an upright position

00:32:12.660 --> 00:32:17.780
and made it a bassy sort
of sound on the left hand

00:32:17.780 --> 00:32:21.590
and on the right hand,
a sharper sound.

00:32:21.590 --> 00:32:27.370
The instrument is made
out of rawhide from goat

00:32:27.370 --> 00:32:31.470
or sheep from-- the same for here.

00:32:31.470 --> 00:32:35.300
And these straps are
also from the same--

00:32:35.300 --> 00:32:36.600
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Material.

00:32:36.600 --> 00:32:38.330
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: -- material.

00:32:38.330 --> 00:32:41.220
However, the chamber
in the left-hand drum

00:32:41.220 --> 00:32:45.480
to create the bassy sound
at that point was wood.

00:32:45.480 --> 00:32:47.340
And then later on, as we--

00:32:47.340 --> 00:32:50.740
as it evolved, it became clay

00:32:50.740 --> 00:32:54.840
because the clay pot was
being played in the south.

00:32:54.840 --> 00:32:58.850
Somebody had this idea that
if we change that to clay,

00:32:58.850 --> 00:33:01.990
the bassy sound would
be even more bassier.

00:33:01.990 --> 00:33:06.400
So, that was experimented
with, it went on for a while.

00:33:06.400 --> 00:33:11.030
If you look at the pictures
of old like 18th century

00:33:11.030 --> 00:33:13.490
or 17th century tabla player,

00:33:13.490 --> 00:33:16.970
you will see they're
either wood or clay.

00:33:16.970 --> 00:33:27.870
It is around 1900 something,
1902, 1903, around that time,

00:33:27.870 --> 00:33:32.490
this experimentation
reached in the brass era.

00:33:32.490 --> 00:33:38.440
So, the brass came to replace
the clay for concert purposes.

00:33:38.440 --> 00:33:39.930
It makes them look good.

00:33:39.930 --> 00:33:41.230
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: OK.

00:33:41.230 --> 00:33:42.530
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: It shines.

00:33:42.530 --> 00:33:46.990
It shines and the sound
gets heavier and heavier.

00:33:46.990 --> 00:33:52.580
And as-- If you notice the old
pictures, you will see that these--

00:33:52.580 --> 00:33:57.020
the drums itself was a lot smaller.

00:33:57.020 --> 00:33:58.320
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: OK.

00:33:58.320 --> 00:34:01.280
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: And
so, as the metal enter--

00:34:01.280 --> 00:34:06.590
as metal entered the picture, you
will notice that it became fuller

00:34:06.590 --> 00:34:13.600 position:56%
and more rounder in shape and the
sound also improved along with that.

00:34:13.600 --> 00:34:18.530
However, in this case, it's still
is wood but they experimented

00:34:18.530 --> 00:34:23.250
with different types of
wood and they found the teak

00:34:23.250 --> 00:34:29.320
or neem wood gives the better
sound when you put the hide on top.

00:34:29.320 --> 00:34:35.320
And the one other thing, there
are lots of experimentation went

00:34:35.320 --> 00:34:37.940
to get the clearer sound.

00:34:37.940 --> 00:34:39.470
[Background sound] There
are actually three sound.

00:34:39.470 --> 00:34:42.610
This keenar sound, which is the
shadj sound and the middle sound

00:34:42.610 --> 00:34:49.130
which is called the maidan
sound, the swara of the tabla.

00:34:49.130 --> 00:34:53.210
And then the black ball sound,
which is the flat sound.

00:34:53.210 --> 00:34:57.920
And then, there's a resonating
sound, the conch shell sound.

00:34:57.920 --> 00:35:04.010
So these four sounds, also
they're in pakhawaj except

00:35:04.010 --> 00:35:06.420
that it's played differently.

00:35:06.420 --> 00:35:10.240
Here, we rely most of
the time on the finger.

00:35:10.240 --> 00:35:14.030
We don't use the entire
hand for the tabla

00:35:14.030 --> 00:35:16.510
and it's difficult in
an upright position.

00:35:16.510 --> 00:35:20.090
However, when you're playing
it like this, you're playing it

00:35:20.090 --> 00:35:22.600
like this, this technique is used.

00:35:22.600 --> 00:35:23.900
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: OK.

00:35:23.900 --> 00:35:25.200
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: So--

