&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Slap.

00:35:26.500 --> 00:35:27.800
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: -- this slap--

00:35:27.800 --> 00:35:29.100
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: That's
start with the pakhawaj.

00:35:29.100 --> 00:35:30.400
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yeah,
that's the pakhawaj style.

00:35:30.400 --> 00:35:31.700
And they've come up with
the same sound [music].

00:35:31.700 --> 00:35:36.310
This sound [music]
and tabla replaced

00:35:36.310 --> 00:35:39.950
that with this sound
[music] and as you can tell

00:35:39.950 --> 00:35:43.300
that this sound is sweeter
than the pakhawaj sound.

00:35:43.300 --> 00:35:46.670 position:56%
So, in terms of the sound technique,

00:35:46.670 --> 00:35:48.500
a lot of experiments
are still being made.

00:35:48.500 --> 00:35:50.180
The Zakir Hussain has come

00:35:50.180 --> 00:35:54.580
up with the fourth finger
sound, he's in tabla.

00:35:54.580 --> 00:35:57.320
And just a little bit
of detail, in tabla,

00:35:57.320 --> 00:36:02.370
this is what we call the workhorse,
this finger, the index finger.

00:36:02.370 --> 00:36:05.440
The middle finger is
called the flat finger,

00:36:05.440 --> 00:36:10.990
which is used for flat sound
also for the swara sound.

00:36:10.990 --> 00:36:17.760 position:56%
The third finger is also used not in
some gharanas, not like in Benares

00:36:17.760 --> 00:36:22.940 position:56%
for example, they don't use the
third finger, they use three finger.

00:36:22.940 --> 00:36:28.180
But in Farrukhabad and
Lucknow, these fingers are used,

00:36:28.180 --> 00:36:31.710
so that the middle and the third.

00:36:31.710 --> 00:36:35.570 position:56%
So, Zakir Hussain has
experimented with this a lot and so,

00:36:35.570 --> 00:36:38.340
he now uses this one also.

00:36:38.340 --> 00:36:44.960
So, there are certain syllables
for playing fast speed syllable.

00:36:44.960 --> 00:36:48.650
He used this many times

00:36:48.650 --> 00:36:51.940
and he showed us the
technique how to use it.

00:36:51.940 --> 00:36:57.310
For example, when there
is a super fast speed

00:36:57.310 --> 00:37:00.370
of teental or 16 beats cycle going.

00:37:00.370 --> 00:37:01.670
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Yup.

00:37:01.670 --> 00:37:04.130
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak:
And he is using it

00:37:04.130 --> 00:37:06.990
and it's creating the
same amount of resonance.

00:37:06.990 --> 00:37:11.420
Of course, it requires
a lot of practice too.

00:37:11.420 --> 00:37:17.680 position:56%
But it's producing the same kind of
tone and the sound for playing that.

00:37:17.680 --> 00:37:25.040
And coming back to your question
on the technique part of it

00:37:25.040 --> 00:37:28.780
that evolved from the
pakhawaj to tabla,

00:37:28.780 --> 00:37:35.460
a lot of changes had been
made in terms of compositions.

00:37:35.460 --> 00:37:41.160
So, the composition that
originated in Delhi that is played

00:37:41.160 --> 00:37:47.440
with two finger has now moved
east which we call purab.

00:37:47.440 --> 00:37:53.110
Purab baj means the style of the
purab, the style of the east.

00:37:53.110 --> 00:37:55.920
Composition has evolved.

00:37:55.920 --> 00:38:02.250 position:56%
Some are used for dance, for dancing
feet, of the court of the maharajas

00:38:02.250 --> 00:38:07.460
and the, you know, different
principality later on.

00:38:07.460 --> 00:38:11.300
Some evolved just for
playing solo purposes.

00:38:11.300 --> 00:38:14.360
There is an entire
repertoire on play--

00:38:14.360 --> 00:38:17.840
for playing tabla solo
which is called peshkar.

00:38:17.840 --> 00:38:25.050
Peshkar came from the same thing
as we understand, you know,

00:38:25.050 --> 00:38:28.950
the rhythmic format
follow a vocal format.

00:38:28.950 --> 00:38:32.020
So in vocal, there is-- when
the instrument is being played,

00:38:32.020 --> 00:38:33.470
there is something called alap,

00:38:33.470 --> 00:38:35.500
there is no rhythmic
expression there.

00:38:35.500 --> 00:38:41.340
So in tabla, peshkar is a
very meditative type movement

00:38:41.340 --> 00:38:44.690
in the finger of drumming.

00:38:44.690 --> 00:38:48.780
And slowly, slowly it
builds it up to kaydas,

00:38:48.780 --> 00:38:52.030
which is a fixed composition
and then to relas

00:38:52.030 --> 00:38:56.020
which is fast composition and
then there are guts which is

00:38:56.020 --> 00:39:02.900
like a composition that is divided
into three cyclical patterns.

00:39:02.900 --> 00:39:04.720
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: And
these are just musical--

00:39:04.720 --> 00:39:06.500
these are solely for tabla?

00:39:06.500 --> 00:39:07.800
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: The tablas.

00:39:07.800 --> 00:39:09.100
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: And
they have a history.

00:39:09.100 --> 00:39:10.400
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yes.

00:39:10.400 --> 00:39:13.770
And the history goes from place
to place to place and as you know

00:39:13.770 --> 00:39:15.620
that those days, there
were no internet,

00:39:15.620 --> 00:39:19.210
there was no trains
or anything like that.

00:39:19.210 --> 00:39:22.680
So, the gharanas grew around Delhi.

00:39:22.680 --> 00:39:28.620 position:56%
So, from Delhi to UP, Uttar Pradesh,
which is the next state adjacent

00:39:28.620 --> 00:39:32.580
to Delhi, these are
where the maharajas

00:39:32.580 --> 00:39:37.400
and their courts were settled
and all the gharanas are

00:39:37.400 --> 00:39:41.150
around like Delhi is the first
then came the Farrukhabad

00:39:41.150 --> 00:39:43.710
and Lucknow, which is the next two.

00:39:43.710 --> 00:39:46.090
And then, a small village next

00:39:46.090 --> 00:39:50.610
to Lucknow is called
Ajrara, which is number four.

00:39:50.610 --> 00:39:54.160
And they all have their
special type of techniques.

00:39:54.160 --> 00:39:57.470
And they specialize
on finger techniques

00:39:57.470 --> 00:40:03.070
and then they teach their students
how to go about performing those.

00:40:03.070 --> 00:40:08.670
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: So, it leads-- you
