00:42:34.300 --> 00:42:39.240
Maybe somewhat closer to jazz
but the other thing I was going

00:42:39.240 --> 00:42:43.170
to say at-- too, when Debu was
talking about the various schools

00:42:43.170 --> 00:42:49.960
of music, is our musical tradition
has been mostly an oral tradition.

00:42:49.960 --> 00:42:51.990
And all of these things that--

00:42:51.990 --> 00:42:55.400
He talked about the various
syllables and, you know,

00:42:55.400 --> 00:43:00.330
whether it's various melodies
or melodic compositions,

00:43:00.330 --> 00:43:07.830 position:56%
up until about 70 years ago there
was no written history of any music.

00:43:07.830 --> 00:43:12.690
It was all passed orally from
one master to their students then

00:43:12.690 --> 00:43:14.210 position:56%
to their students to their students.

00:43:14.210 --> 00:43:15.800
It's amazing if you think about it.

00:43:15.800 --> 00:43:23.310 position:56%
And for a person to retain that
kind of music, whether it be melodic

00:43:23.310 --> 00:43:28.540 position:56%
or rhythmic or whatever have you,
in their minds and heads and to able

00:43:28.540 --> 00:43:32.410
to pass that from generation to
generation without losing it,

00:43:32.410 --> 00:43:36.590
it's an amazing accomplishment,
human accomplishment.

00:43:36.590 --> 00:43:40.850
But then, you know, when music
was more formalized and especially

00:43:40.850 --> 00:43:44.620
after independence of India when
it was being taught more openly

00:43:44.620 --> 00:43:48.980
in schools, there was a
need to document that.

00:43:48.980 --> 00:43:54.240
And so, annotation
system came by but it--

00:43:54.240 --> 00:43:59.670
again, so, because it was
an oral tradition, there's--

00:43:59.670 --> 00:44:05.450
there was a lot of freedom
given to both the precautionist,

00:44:05.450 --> 00:44:08.320
the instrumentalist or
the vocalist to express.

00:44:08.320 --> 00:44:12.020
It's a way of self expressing,
of course, there are boundaries,

00:44:12.020 --> 00:44:17.120
there's definitely grammatical
nuances of how you move

00:44:17.120 --> 00:44:19.800
around whether it's a
raag or a taal scale.

00:44:19.800 --> 00:44:26.610
But then, it is all up to the
artist or artists to find ways

00:44:26.610 --> 00:44:29.370
of expression within
those boundaries.

00:44:29.370 --> 00:44:36.090
And so, if I play a certain
raag that has a certain scale,

00:44:36.090 --> 00:44:39.810
I liken that to a scale
in western music.

00:44:39.810 --> 00:44:43.180
But it is not like as formal
scale like you know it

00:44:43.180 --> 00:44:46.270 position:56%
like you're playing a C minor scale.

00:44:46.270 --> 00:44:50.750 position:56%
Because even within the same scale,
there could be three different raags

00:44:50.750 --> 00:44:58.120
and just the nuances created by
the rest notes and certain ways

00:44:58.120 --> 00:45:03.010
that you move around creates a
whole different experience for--

00:45:03.010 --> 00:45:05.890
from an audience perspective.

