So, I'm in the key of C and
that's where I'm going to--

00:46:23.990 --> 00:46:29.970
this matches my Sa and his swar.

00:46:29.970 --> 00:46:31.630
So, we're all in sync together.

00:46:31.630 --> 00:46:33.190
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Right.

00:46:33.190 --> 00:46:37.800
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: So, what
I'm going to do is play something

00:46:37.800 --> 00:46:46.750
that is in the key of or
the thaat called khamaj.

00:46:46.750 --> 00:46:53.510
And I'm going to play what the
khamaj that, the notes are.

00:46:53.510 --> 00:47:02.040
[ Music ]

00:47:02.040 --> 00:47:06.790
So, plain, do, re, mi,
fa, so, la, ti, do.

00:47:06.790 --> 00:47:11.110
The only difference is that
when I came back down the scale,

00:47:11.110 --> 00:47:14.510
I used the flatter seventh note.

00:47:14.510 --> 00:47:20.040
[ Music ]

00:47:20.040 --> 00:47:29.730
Now, using that and just by
removing certain things from--

00:47:29.730 --> 00:47:32.850
as I go up certain notes
from the ascending--

00:47:32.850 --> 00:47:36.700
from I ascend and then
positioning certain other notes,

00:47:36.700 --> 00:47:39.180
I can create a raag.

00:47:39.180 --> 00:47:44.370
For example, if I omit
the second note in--

00:47:44.370 --> 00:47:48.510
on my way up, which is
the [music] and just play.

00:47:48.510 --> 00:47:55.040
[ Music ]

00:47:55.040 --> 00:47:59.780
I've create-- this is raag
khamaj, which is very close

00:47:59.780 --> 00:48:01.940
to thaat khamaj but
it's very different.

00:48:01.940 --> 00:48:05.330
So, I'm just going
to play a little--

00:48:05.330 --> 00:48:08.510
a few bars then you can get
the essence of this raga.

00:48:08.510 --> 00:48:40.040
[ Music ]

00:48:40.040 --> 00:48:42.290
So, that's khamaj.

00:48:42.290 --> 00:48:48.040
Now, what if I use-- instead of
the-- omitting the second note,

00:48:48.040 --> 00:48:50.150
I actually going to use the second.

00:48:50.150 --> 00:48:52.940
I'm going to omit the third note

00:48:52.940 --> 00:48:57.510
and the sixth note
and let it sound like.

00:48:57.510 --> 00:49:30.040
[ Music ]

00:49:30.040 --> 00:49:32.280
That's a very different
melodic picture

00:49:32.280 --> 00:49:38.180
as you can well appreciate
to a khamaj.

00:49:38.180 --> 00:49:40.190
And it's called Rag Desh.

00:49:40.190 --> 00:49:45.150
So, using the same scale, I can go
from rag to rag to rag and then,

00:49:45.150 --> 00:49:49.270
in some cases, you
know, there are notes--

00:49:49.270 --> 00:49:55.180 position:56%
additional notes that are introduced
that are not natural to the scale,

00:49:55.180 --> 00:49:58.350
they're called [inaudible]
swars or conflicting notes.

00:49:58.350 --> 00:50:03.510
So, for example, again, sticking
to the same thaat of khamaj.

00:50:03.510 --> 00:50:17.040
[ Music ]

00:50:17.040 --> 00:50:20.150
Now, I've gone into another raag

00:50:20.150 --> 00:50:24.280
that again has a different
melodic appeal,

00:50:24.280 --> 00:50:25.870
it's called raag jaijaiwanti.

00:50:25.870 --> 00:50:28.800
And this goes on and on and on.

00:50:28.800 --> 00:50:30.100
So--

00:50:30.100 --> 00:50:31.400
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: So,
the thaat is the scale?

00:50:31.400 --> 00:50:32.700
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty:
The thaat is the scale.

00:50:32.700 --> 00:50:34.030
So, it's seven notes.

00:50:34.030 --> 00:50:36.050
[ Music ]

00:50:36.050 --> 00:50:39.680
And within that, I can
layer in different notes

00:50:39.680 --> 00:50:44.470
and also the way I am
playing those notes

00:50:44.470 --> 00:50:48.060
and accentuating certain notes.

00:50:48.060 --> 00:50:52.810
Like for example, the
khamaj raag was based

00:50:52.810 --> 00:50:55.220
where there was more accent

00:50:55.220 --> 00:51:00.510
on the third note [music]
and the seventh note.

00:51:00.510 --> 00:51:17.040
[ Music ]

00:51:17.040 --> 00:51:22.630 position:56%
Whereas, in raag desh, the accent is
on the re which is the second note

00:51:22.630 --> 00:51:27.510
and the mi which is
the seventh note.

00:51:27.510 --> 00:51:36.040
[ Music ]

00:51:36.040 --> 00:51:39.950
So, there you can see that that--

00:51:39.950 --> 00:51:44.000
and the two sentiments
of the two raags

00:51:44.000 --> 00:51:47.390
in the melodies are very different.

00:51:47.390 --> 00:51:52.740
And that's how the
raags get developed.

00:51:52.740 --> 00:51:57.170
And it's-- These are
traditional raags and of course,

00:51:57.170 --> 00:51:59.990
people tend to blend
different things

00:51:59.990 --> 00:52:04.170
and create their own
raags in certain cases.

00:52:04.170 --> 00:52:08.750
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: How do
you decide what kind of--

00:52:08.750 --> 00:52:20.450
what drum cycle or thaat is
going to be played with--

00:52:20.450 --> 00:52:32.300
how do you guys decide that
with the raag if, you know,

00:52:32.300 --> 00:52:34.490
if you're going to perform?

00:52:34.490 --> 00:52:41.230
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: That depends on
the composition that it's set to.

00:52:41.230 --> 00:52:47.000
And that comes from the
person who has composed it.

00:52:47.000 --> 00:52:48.300
It could be him.

00:52:48.300 --> 00:52:49.600
It could be his guru--

00:52:49.600 --> 00:52:50.900
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: OK.

00:52:50.900 --> 00:52:52.200
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: -- or it
could be his guru but some raags

00:52:52.200 --> 00:52:57.070
that are like-- it's always been
like that that came for ages.

00:52:57.070 --> 00:52:59.310
And that--

00:52:59.310 --> 00:53:04.550
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: That it always
has a specific beat cycle.

00:53:04.550 --> 00:53:06.000
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak:
Yeah, a specific set.

00:53:06.000 --> 00:53:07.300
Yeah.

00:53:07.300 --> 00:53:08.600
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Yeah.

00:53:08.600 --> 00:53:13.390
But I mean, technically, you
could play any raag in any cycle.

00:53:13.390 --> 00:53:16.280
And, often, there used to
be a healthy competition

00:53:16.280 --> 00:53:19.170
in the olden days when
the instrumentalist

00:53:19.170 --> 00:53:24.610
or vocalist would start playing
and would look at the percussionist

00:53:24.610 --> 00:53:25.910
to catch up and figure out.

00:53:25.910 --> 00:53:27.650
Like--

00:53:27.650 --> 00:53:28.950
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yeah.

00:53:28.950 --> 00:53:33.890
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: --
you need to figure out where.

00:53:33.890 --> 00:53:38.640
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: And that
it's like a hide and seek game.

00:53:38.640 --> 00:53:42.910
You know, the tabla player, the
rhythm person is trying to figure

00:53:42.910 --> 00:53:46.630
out what taal or what
structure it is set to.

00:53:46.630 --> 00:53:48.070
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Yeah.

00:53:48.070 --> 00:53:59.360 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: And sometimes,
it takes almost three, four cycles--

00:53:59.360 --> 00:54:01.930
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty:
To figure that out.

00:54:01.930 --> 00:54:08.140
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Naya: --
to figure that out.

00:54:08.140 --> 00:54:16.320
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: And does that
create sort of a healthy tension

00:54:16.320 --> 00:54:19.080
within the-- between
the two players?

00:54:19.080 --> 00:54:20.400
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: It is.

00:54:20.400 --> 00:54:21.700
It is.

00:54:21.700 --> 00:54:23.000
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: It is.

00:54:23.000 --> 00:54:24.720
It's all playful--

00:54:24.720 --> 00:54:26.020
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Yeah.

00:54:26.020 --> 00:54:27.320
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: --

00:54:27.320 --> 00:54:30.930
but the idea is that if
you're worth your training

00:54:30.930 --> 00:54:33.670
that you should be able
to figure that out.

00:54:33.670 --> 00:54:40.260
Nowadays of course, people
discuss it and play, you know,

00:54:40.260 --> 00:54:46.890
beforehand when they were warming
up for that-- before the concert,

00:54:46.890 --> 00:54:49.420
they'll have a discussion.

00:54:49.420 --> 00:54:54.170
And so, I would tell him, "Hey,
I'm going to play sevens,"

00:54:54.170 --> 00:54:58.110
or "I'm going to play 16th."

00:54:58.110 --> 00:54:59.410
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: But would--

00:54:59.410 --> 00:55:03.460
So, the instrumentalist would
always have a good grounding

00:55:03.460 --> 00:55:05.450
in the percussion?

00:55:05.450 --> 00:55:07.900
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty:
Yeah and I think--

00:55:07.900 --> 00:55:11.920
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: But are you
unusual and that you have had--

00:55:11.920 --> 00:55:13.220
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: No, no.

00:55:13.220 --> 00:55:17.230
I think it's part of our training,
and it goes the same way with the--

00:55:17.230 --> 00:55:19.630
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Could
you turn that off?

00:55:19.630 --> 00:55:20.930
Yeah.

00:55:20.930 --> 00:55:23.290
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty:
It goes the same way

00:55:23.290 --> 00:55:24.610
with the percussionist also.

00:55:24.610 --> 00:55:27.910
He talked about learning
vocal music.

00:55:27.910 --> 00:55:32.390
I think, the total training
of Indian music consists

00:55:32.390 --> 00:55:36.120 position:56%
of the vocal component, the
percussion of the rhythmic component

00:55:36.120 --> 00:55:38.750
and then if you are
playing an instrument,

00:55:38.750 --> 00:55:41.120
you learn some other instrument.

00:55:41.120 --> 00:55:42.420
In some cases--

00:55:42.420 --> 00:55:46.040 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Actually, what I
was going to say is that, you know,

00:55:46.040 --> 00:55:48.830
internally, when I'm
performing with somebody,

00:55:48.830 --> 00:55:50.670
I'm actually singing inside.

00:55:50.670 --> 00:55:51.970
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Oh really?

00:55:51.970 --> 00:55:53.270
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yeah.

00:55:53.270 --> 00:55:56.570
And, you know, and I'm also playing
it through my hand but internally,

00:55:56.570 --> 00:56:00.080
I'm actually doing-- going
through the singing part and sort

00:56:00.080 --> 00:56:03.850
of layering the rhythm on top of
it, which I could hear internally.

00:56:03.850 --> 00:56:05.300
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Of
course, you have.

00:56:05.300 --> 00:56:06.600
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Yeah.

00:56:06.600 --> 00:56:07.900
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yeah.

00:56:07.900 --> 00:56:11.800
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: And
the melody is very important

00:56:11.800 --> 00:56:17.920 position:56%
because not two melody is the same
and the type of theka that he talked

00:56:17.920 --> 00:56:26.640
about earlier, you know, it varies
based on the type of melody.

00:56:26.640 --> 00:56:29.150
So, in case we have rehearsed it

00:56:29.150 --> 00:56:40.100
and he has heard the melody then he
would probably have figured it out.

00:56:40.100 --> 00:56:44.960
But if we hadn't met each other
and we're meeting first time

00:56:44.960 --> 00:56:51.830
on stage then it is really up
to the percussionist to listen

00:56:51.830 --> 00:56:57.580
and that's why it is
so important to listen

00:56:57.580 --> 00:57:00.000
to each other and figure it out.

00:57:00.000 --> 00:57:03.940
Again, I say this going
back to what I said earlier.

00:57:03.940 --> 00:57:05.490
It's and old tradition.

00:57:05.490 --> 00:57:06.790
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yeah.

00:57:06.790 --> 00:57:08.090
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty:
It is based on--

00:57:08.090 --> 00:57:10.740
and you asked a question as
to how do you keep in sync?

00:57:10.740 --> 00:57:12.460
It's by hearing.

00:57:12.460 --> 00:57:13.760
We are not looking--

00:57:13.760 --> 00:57:16.650
Well, sometimes, we make eye
contact but mostly we're-- I'm--

00:57:16.650 --> 00:57:17.950
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak:
You're listening.

00:57:17.950 --> 00:57:20.050
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: -- listening
to where he's coming in terms

00:57:20.050 --> 00:57:24.120
of his rhythmic cycle and where
I'm at and we're communicating.

00:57:24.120 --> 00:57:26.520
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: And basically,
what the music is saying.

00:57:26.520 --> 00:57:27.820
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Yeah.

00:57:27.820 --> 00:57:30.910 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: So, could we--
would it be possible for you to play

00:57:30.910 --> 00:57:34.640
and you to figure out what the--

00:57:34.640 --> 00:57:35.940
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Sure.

00:57:35.940 --> 00:57:37.240
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: -- cycle is?

00:57:37.240 --> 00:57:38.540
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Yeah.

00:57:38.540 --> 00:57:39.840
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yeah.

00:57:39.840 --> 00:57:41.140
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Can
we-- and see that?

00:57:41.140 --> 00:57:44.050
&gt;&gt; And you can turn the drum back.

00:57:44.050 --> 00:57:45.540
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: And you can turn--

00:57:45.540 --> 00:57:46.840
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Yes.

00:57:46.840 --> 00:57:48.930
Yeah, of course, I will.

00:57:48.930 --> 00:57:50.490
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: And I just--

00:57:50.490 --> 00:57:54.480
I was just going to
say one funny incident

00:57:54.480 --> 00:57:57.400
that happened two weeks ago.

00:57:57.400 --> 00:58:02.450
There is a vocalist, I think, I
send you guys the invite to that.

00:58:02.450 --> 00:58:03.750
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Yeah.

00:58:03.750 --> 00:58:05.050
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: The
vocalist came from Kolkata

00:58:05.050 --> 00:58:07.550
and she is a young vocalist and
I have never heard her before.

00:58:07.550 --> 00:58:09.520
I've heard over the
internet and stuff

00:58:09.520 --> 00:58:11.650
but I've never heard
her real concert.

00:58:11.650 --> 00:58:15.150 position:56%
And she started singing a
particular bandish, a particular gut

00:58:15.150 --> 00:58:18.910
in 12 beats, but it's
faster 12 beats.

00:58:18.910 --> 00:58:22.370
But the 12 beats sounded
like 16 beats.

00:58:22.370 --> 00:58:24.090
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Because
she was singing fast?

00:58:24.090 --> 00:58:26.560
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak:
She was singing fast.

00:58:26.560 --> 00:58:29.600
To me, it was more like 16 than 12.

00:58:29.600 --> 00:58:34.090
And she was singing it in
such a way that it was sort

00:58:34.090 --> 00:58:35.600
of to play with me, I guess.

00:58:35.600 --> 00:58:36.900
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Yeah.

00:58:36.900 --> 00:58:38.200
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak:
That was the idea.

00:58:38.200 --> 00:58:40.310
And a lot of time, it's accepted,
that we don't know each other.

00:58:40.310 --> 00:58:43.240
We are playing for the first time,
coming here for the first time

00:58:43.240 --> 00:58:50.610
and then we perform and we
haven't had a rehearsal.

00:58:50.610 --> 00:58:54.070 position:56%
So, that happened and I picked up 16

00:58:54.070 --> 00:58:56.790
and then she said,
"No, no, it's 12."

00:58:56.790 --> 00:58:58.090
So then--

00:58:58.090 --> 00:59:00.380
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: And how did she
say that while she's singing?

00:59:00.380 --> 00:59:01.680
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Well--

00:59:01.680 --> 00:59:02.980
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak:
No, she just whispered.

00:59:02.980 --> 00:59:04.280
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Whispered.

00:59:04.280 --> 00:59:05.580
OK.

00:59:05.580 --> 00:59:06.880
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yeah.

00:59:06.880 --> 00:59:08.180
But it's all part and
parcel of the game.

00:59:08.180 --> 00:59:09.480
I mean, you're not
supposed to know everything.

00:59:09.480 --> 00:59:10.780
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Yeah.

00:59:10.780 --> 00:59:12.080
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Yeah.

00:59:12.080 --> 00:59:13.380
That's good.

00:59:13.380 --> 00:59:14.680
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: So yeah.

00:59:14.680 --> 00:59:15.980
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: So let--

00:59:15.980 --> 00:59:17.280
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: And there's
another funny story I would tell

00:59:17.280 --> 00:59:18.580
if we have the time.

00:59:18.580 --> 00:59:19.880
This is in many, many years ago,

00:59:19.880 --> 00:59:21.180
when Pandit Ravi Shankar
was a very young man.

00:59:21.180 --> 00:59:22.480 position:56%
He and then, there was a very famous
tabla player Pandit Samta Prasad.

00:59:22.480 --> 00:59:23.780
They were playing in
a concert in Kolkata.

00:59:23.780 --> 00:59:25.080 position:56%
And they were in the living room and
Pandit Ravi Shankar had practiced

00:59:25.080 --> 00:59:26.380
with him something
in 16 beats cycle.

00:59:26.380 --> 00:59:27.680
When he went on stage--

00:59:27.680 --> 00:59:28.980
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: He changed.

00:59:28.980 --> 00:59:30.280
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty:
-- he changed it

00:59:30.280 --> 00:59:31.580
to a 15 beat cycle called pancham
sawari, the same composition.

00:59:31.580 --> 00:59:32.880 position:56%
He played with the same composition,
he just pick away one note and,

00:59:32.880 --> 00:59:34.180
you know, that made it
to a 15 composition.

00:59:34.180 --> 00:59:35.480
Now, Samta Prasad had being heard
this thing-- and this was just,

00:59:35.480 --> 00:59:36.780
you know, Ravi Shankar
playing with Samta Prasad.

00:59:36.780 --> 00:59:38.080
He took off on a run
and without realizing

00:59:38.080 --> 00:59:39.380
that Ravi Shankar is
playing pancham sawari.

00:59:39.380 --> 00:59:40.680
It's the same composition, and
just think of the brilliance

00:59:40.680 --> 00:59:41.980
of the man that-- and of course he
lands on some place and, you know,

00:59:41.980 --> 00:59:43.280
Ravi Shankar some-- and
this happened a few times

00:59:43.280 --> 00:59:44.580
and in front of a live audience.

00:59:44.580 --> 00:59:45.880
So then, Samta Prasad just,
you know, stopped playing.

00:59:45.880 --> 00:59:47.180
And then-- And almost Ravi Shankar
would, you know, smile at him

00:59:47.180 --> 00:59:48.480
and said, this is pancham
sawari and then they continued.

00:59:48.480 --> 00:59:49.780
But the-- it emphasizes the point
of listening and the concept

00:59:49.780 --> 00:59:51.080
of listening to each other.

00:59:51.080 --> 00:59:52.380
Yeah.

00:59:52.380 --> 00:59:53.680
&gt;&gt; I just had a question about--

00:59:53.680 --> 00:59:54.980
but then, you can ask
and they can edit it,

00:59:54.980 --> 00:59:56.280
about the vocalization you said
that you sing while you play along.

00:59:56.280 --> 00:59:57.580
Are you vocalizing?

00:59:57.580 --> 00:59:58.880
Are you singing words?

00:59:58.880 --> 01:00:00.180
Are you?

01:00:00.180 --> 01:00:01.480
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: I'm
just singing the melody.

01:00:01.480 --> 01:00:02.780
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Which is--

01:00:02.780 --> 01:00:04.080
&gt;&gt; You're singing the--

01:00:04.080 --> 01:00:05.380
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: You-- he--

01:00:05.380 --> 01:00:06.680
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: I'm
just singing internally.

01:00:06.680 --> 01:00:07.980
I'm not, you know, letting it out.

01:00:07.980 --> 01:00:09.280
&gt;&gt; But--

01:00:09.280 --> 01:00:10.580
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: But on
the tabla, I am layering it

01:00:10.580 --> 01:00:11.880
on that part that I'm
singing inside.

01:00:11.880 --> 01:00:13.180
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Are
you singing syllables?

01:00:13.180 --> 01:00:14.480
Are you singing--

01:00:14.480 --> 01:00:15.780
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak:
Just the melody itself.

01:00:15.780 --> 01:00:17.080
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Just the melody.

01:00:17.080 --> 01:00:18.380
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yeah.

01:00:18.380 --> 01:00:19.680
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Just--

01:00:19.680 --> 01:00:20.980
&gt;&gt; And when you would listen to
your grandfather and his students,

01:00:20.980 --> 01:00:22.280
were they vocalizing--
they were vocalizing loud--

01:00:22.280 --> 01:00:23.580
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yes.

01:00:23.580 --> 01:00:24.880
&gt;&gt; Is that right?

01:00:24.880 --> 01:00:26.180
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yes.

01:00:26.180 --> 01:00:27.480
Yes, and during the rehearsal or
during the-- and it happens a lot.

01:00:27.480 --> 01:00:28.780
I mean, let's say for example,

01:00:28.780 --> 01:00:30.080
he's going to play a raag
that is set to 7 beats.

01:00:30.080 --> 01:00:31.380
And the seven is not always clear
or accented, the seventh note,

01:00:31.380 --> 01:00:32.680
you know, where it's
hitting the very first note.

01:00:32.680 --> 01:00:33.980
In tabla language, it's called sum.

01:00:33.980 --> 01:00:35.280
And the sum is not
very clear where the--

01:00:35.280 --> 01:00:40.130
in the gut or the bandish
is starting.

01:00:40.130 --> 01:00:42.110
And it's purposely done that way.

01:00:42.110 --> 01:00:46.300
The composer have that in mind
that I want to keep it that way,

01:00:46.300 --> 01:00:47.940
I want to create it that way.

01:00:47.940 --> 01:00:49.990
And that's the beauty
of the history.

01:00:49.990 --> 01:00:51.290
That's the mystery.

01:00:51.290 --> 01:00:55.920
And so, when that was being done it
is creating confusion in the mind

01:00:55.920 --> 01:01:00.300
of the tabla player so we
clear that up either the end

01:01:00.300 --> 01:01:04.950
of the learning process
or during the rehearsal.

01:01:04.950 --> 01:01:08.880
But imagine if it is not
cleared up in either way,

01:01:08.880 --> 01:01:11.730
so we clear it up on stage.

01:01:11.730 --> 01:01:14.860
So that there's no confusion

01:01:14.860 --> 01:01:17.890
&gt;&gt; And does-- When
your vocalist came,

01:01:17.890 --> 01:01:20.300
was she vocalizing with syllables?

01:01:20.300 --> 01:01:21.600
Or was she singing chords?

01:01:21.600 --> 01:01:22.900
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Yeah
that's the question --

01:01:22.900 --> 01:01:27.540 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: She was
singing-- vocalizing with the words.

01:01:27.540 --> 01:01:28.840
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Yeah.

01:01:28.840 --> 01:01:30.140
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yeah.

01:01:30.140 --> 01:01:31.440
&gt;&gt; So you were-- with
some compositions,

01:01:31.440 --> 01:01:32.740
there are words, poetry--

01:01:32.740 --> 01:01:34.040
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yes.

01:01:34.040 --> 01:01:35.340
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Yeah.

01:01:35.340 --> 01:01:36.640
Vocal music has a, you know,
obviously has a language.

01:01:36.640 --> 01:01:41.310
Instrumental music does not have
a language and, you know, again,

01:01:41.310 --> 01:01:45.310
there are two syllables in
sarod and you can create a lot

01:01:45.310 --> 01:01:47.010
of different patterns with it.

01:01:47.010 --> 01:01:49.740
But there's no language per se.

01:01:49.740 --> 01:01:51.560
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: But you do
say [inaudible] for singing?

01:01:51.560 --> 01:01:52.860
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Yeah.

01:01:52.860 --> 01:01:56.060 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: And then, for tabla
you have different vocalization?

01:01:56.060 --> 01:01:57.360
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Phrases.

01:01:57.360 --> 01:01:58.660
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Phrases and for --

01:01:58.660 --> 01:01:59.960
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty:
But vocal music also--

01:01:59.960 --> 01:02:01.260
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: And for a sarod,

01:02:01.260 --> 01:02:02.560
do you have different
phrases or different--

01:02:02.560 --> 01:02:03.860
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Yeah.

01:02:03.860 --> 01:02:05.160
So, we have two syllables.

01:02:05.160 --> 01:02:09.980 position:56%
So, as I said, the down stroke which
is the [music] and the up stroke

01:02:09.980 --> 01:02:13.060
which is the [music] and then,
with that, you can create--

01:02:13.060 --> 01:02:15.100
[ Music ]

01:02:15.100 --> 01:02:18.210
-- various types of pattern.

01:02:18.210 --> 01:02:20.400
[ Humming ]

01:02:20.400 --> 01:02:25.080
But the point is that you can
layer it into any kind of music.

01:02:25.080 --> 01:02:26.380
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Yeah.

01:02:26.380 --> 01:02:28.100
And your vocalizations would be--

01:02:28.100 --> 01:02:31.700
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: My vocalization
in terms of melodic part--

01:02:31.700 --> 01:02:33.000
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: For the tabla.

01:02:33.000 --> 01:02:35.530
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: --
for the tabla is going

01:02:35.530 --> 01:02:39.280
to see how it is matching
the melodic part that,

01:02:39.280 --> 01:02:40.810
the tabla language is different.

01:02:40.810 --> 01:02:42.110
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Yeah which is?

01:02:42.110 --> 01:02:43.860
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: For
example, if I'm playing a na

01:02:43.860 --> 01:02:50.140
which is this [music] or na tin tin
na [music] or na ton ton na [music]

01:02:50.140 --> 01:02:57.290
or na te de [music], all of these
is matching the melodic part.

01:02:57.290 --> 01:02:58.590
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: OK.

01:02:58.590 --> 01:02:59.890
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: OK.

01:02:59.890 --> 01:03:01.190
So, the melodic part
has Sa Re Ga Ma.

01:03:01.190 --> 01:03:02.490
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Right,
which is the voice.

01:03:02.490 --> 01:03:04.910
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: And like he
said, there's seven notes, right?

01:03:04.910 --> 01:03:06.210
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Yeah.

01:03:06.210 --> 01:03:09.240
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: I can match
those seven notes and come

01:03:09.240 --> 01:03:12.490
up with a particular
rhythmic structure, right?

01:03:12.490 --> 01:03:18.490 position:56%
But I am humming it internally to
match my rhythmic structure to that.

01:03:18.490 --> 01:03:19.820
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty:
But also, I think,

01:03:19.820 --> 01:03:24.360
part of Yasmeen's question was
that you do have like a ball--

01:03:24.360 --> 01:03:25.660
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yes, yes.

01:03:25.660 --> 01:03:26.960
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Yeah.

01:03:26.960 --> 01:03:28.260
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: That the
ball is the rhythmic pattern.

01:03:28.260 --> 01:03:29.560
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Right.

01:03:29.560 --> 01:03:30.860
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty:
And that's also recited.

01:03:30.860 --> 01:03:32.160
So, there is an oral
tradition of that.

01:03:32.160 --> 01:03:35.460
So, it is said in tabla and I
know this because I learned it

01:03:35.460 --> 01:03:39.900
for a few years that you can only
play it if you can recite it.

01:03:39.900 --> 01:03:42.450
And you can only play it fast
if you can recite it fast.

01:03:42.450 --> 01:03:43.750
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yes.

01:03:43.750 --> 01:03:46.330
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: But as a tabla
player, you have to know your balls

01:03:46.330 --> 01:03:53.060
as well as the melodic balls
and-- so, that's a lot of--

01:03:53.060 --> 01:03:55.910
and if you got a down set and
the down set has different --

01:03:55.910 --> 01:03:57.210
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Right.

01:03:57.210 --> 01:03:58.510
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: melodic balls --

01:03:58.510 --> 01:03:59.810
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yes, yeah.

01:03:59.810 --> 01:04:01.110
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: -- and so, you
got to know what all of that means

01:04:01.110 --> 01:04:02.410
and how it relates to everything.

01:04:02.410 --> 01:04:03.710
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Aboslutely.

01:04:03.710 --> 01:04:05.010
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: --
which is pretty complex.

01:04:05.010 --> 01:04:06.310
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Yeah.

01:04:06.310 --> 01:04:11.070
And the fun part of it
is it's often improvised.

01:04:11.070 --> 01:04:15.560
I can't remember if it was at
the concert that I played here

01:04:15.560 --> 01:04:22.480
or at some other concert, in a very
fast section of the composition,

01:04:22.480 --> 01:04:24.720
we were exchanging
balls with each other.

01:04:24.720 --> 01:04:26.020
So I was--

01:04:26.020 --> 01:04:27.670
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: I think
it was here [inaudible].

01:04:27.670 --> 01:04:28.970
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Yeah.

01:04:28.970 --> 01:04:30.270
So, it's like a Q&amp;A.

01:04:30.270 --> 01:04:31.570
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Right.

01:04:31.570 --> 01:04:32.870
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: And
so-- And, you know, I'm playing

01:04:32.870 --> 01:04:35.290
and he is responding and
then we come together.

01:04:35.290 --> 01:04:39.610
So, that is done very common
and it's a tradition that came

01:04:39.610 --> 01:04:43.790
from mostly from dance
and the percussion is,

01:04:43.790 --> 01:04:46.910
but it also has crept its way
through instrumental music.

01:04:46.910 --> 01:04:48.210
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yeah.

01:04:48.210 --> 01:04:49.510
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: That's
pretty interesting.

01:04:49.510 --> 01:04:50.810
So, should we try and see if you--

01:04:50.810 --> 01:04:52.110
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Sure.

01:04:52.110 --> 01:04:55.060
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: -- can figure
out what Soumya is playing.

01:04:55.060 --> 01:04:56.820 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: So, I'm going

01:04:56.820 --> 01:05:00.330
to play a few traditional
compositions.

01:05:00.330 --> 01:05:09.080
[Background Music] And there is
one composition that he likes a lot

01:05:09.080 --> 01:05:14.050
and this one you can see-- this
is a very traditional composition

01:05:14.050 --> 01:05:20.640
by a famous maestro in my school
many, many generations ago.

01:05:20.640 --> 01:05:26.550
And it's set to 16
beat in the raag kamod.

01:05:26.550 --> 01:05:30.450
But if you listen to it and
you can see the unusual pattern

01:05:30.450 --> 01:05:32.380
in this-- with this count--

01:05:32.380 --> 01:05:33.680
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak:
I say that this--

01:05:33.680 --> 01:05:34.980
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: So--

01:05:34.980 --> 01:05:37.550
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: -- composition
was in the tabla language.

01:05:37.550 --> 01:05:38.850
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: OK.

01:05:38.850 --> 01:05:40.480
So, it may not be 16 beats
is what you're saying?

01:05:40.480 --> 01:05:41.780
You've got to figure it out?

01:05:41.780 --> 01:05:43.080
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: No, it is
16 beats but you don't know

01:05:43.080 --> 01:05:44.380
where the beginning
and where the end.

01:05:44.380 --> 01:05:46.910
&gt;&gt; But you don't know where the
beginning and where the end.

01:05:46.910 --> 01:05:48.210
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Yeah.

01:05:48.210 --> 01:05:49.510
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: So, that
would be kind of interesting

01:05:49.510 --> 01:05:50.810
if you talked through it as well --

01:05:50.810 --> 01:05:52.110
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Yup

01:05:52.110 --> 01:05:53.410
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yeah.

01:05:53.410 --> 01:05:55.210
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: --
while your playing it.

01:05:55.210 --> 01:08:00.050
[ Music ]

01:08:00.050 --> 01:08:02.980
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: This is
the part where we're improvising

01:08:02.980 --> 01:08:05.690
like rather he knows nor
I know where we're going.

01:08:05.690 --> 01:08:06.990
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yeah.

01:08:06.990 --> 01:08:08.290 position:56%
So, this is the unknown [inaudible].

01:08:08.290 --> 01:08:09.590
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: So,

01:08:09.590 --> 01:08:12.980
what I played up until now is the
fixed part of the composition.

01:08:12.980 --> 01:08:14.280
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: OK.

01:08:14.280 --> 01:08:18.030
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: And you
could hear in that composition

01:08:18.030 --> 01:08:21.870
that it has this unusual of stop
in the middle, unusual pause.

01:08:21.870 --> 01:08:26.790
And if you are not-- if you haven't
heard that composition before--

01:08:26.790 --> 01:08:28.090
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yeah.

01:08:28.090 --> 01:08:31.100
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: -- it is
very difficult to figure it out.

01:08:31.100 --> 01:08:33.890
But it, you know, in the olden
days, it used to be played on stage

01:08:33.890 --> 01:08:36.060
and yeah you figure it out and--

01:08:36.060 --> 01:08:37.360
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yeah.

01:08:37.360 --> 01:08:38.660
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty:
-- come along.

01:08:38.660 --> 01:08:39.960
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Yeah.

01:08:39.960 --> 01:08:41.260 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: So, it starts
from the, you know, the first beat

01:08:41.260 --> 01:08:46.100
and he and I have practiced a few
times, played this on many concerts

01:08:46.100 --> 01:08:49.960
so he knew exactly
which composition it is.

01:08:49.960 --> 01:08:52.490
This is like the melodic
part of it, so he knows that.

01:08:52.490 --> 01:08:53.790
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: So, you know,

01:08:53.790 --> 01:08:56.180
translating that into
a tabla player's mind.

01:08:56.180 --> 01:08:57.480
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Right.

01:08:57.480 --> 01:08:59.280 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: So, I'm thinking

01:08:59.280 --> 01:09:04.560
[ Humming ]

01:09:04.560 --> 01:09:07.190
Yeah, that's where the gap is.

01:09:07.190 --> 01:09:08.490
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty:
That's the stop.

01:09:08.490 --> 01:09:09.790
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak:
That's where the stop is

01:09:09.790 --> 01:09:11.090
which is making the melody so nice.

01:09:11.090 --> 01:09:16.620
But that's also a marking point for
me that is where this beat goes.

01:09:16.620 --> 01:09:17.920
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: OK.

01:09:17.920 --> 01:09:19.220
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: OK.

01:09:19.220 --> 01:09:20.520
Which is my marking for that area.

01:09:20.520 --> 01:09:22.670
And after that, I don't know
what's going to happen, OK.

01:09:22.670 --> 01:09:25.840
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: And what reaches
that that goes into the empty spot.

01:09:25.840 --> 01:09:30.400
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: So that, going
after the ninth or the tenth.

01:09:30.400 --> 01:09:31.700
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: OK.

01:09:31.700 --> 01:09:33.000
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: OK.

01:09:33.000 --> 01:09:34.300
So, we are fluctuating between
that and then moving away.

01:09:34.300 --> 01:09:39.680
And then he could [inaudible]
area and I have no idea.

01:09:39.680 --> 01:09:42.520
I'm just keeping the theka alive.

01:09:42.520 --> 01:09:44.960
If you move the theka,
it's completely lost.

01:09:44.960 --> 01:09:46.260
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Yeah.

01:09:46.260 --> 01:09:49.260
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: And I'm,
also as an instrumentalist,

01:09:49.260 --> 01:09:50.650
listening for what he is playing

01:09:50.650 --> 01:09:53.450
and I'm layering my
music to go with that.

01:09:53.450 --> 01:09:56.640
So, there's a lot of-- that's
why we call it as a conversation.

01:09:56.640 --> 01:10:00.060
And often, in a concert you don't
pick that up but there's a lot

01:10:00.060 --> 01:10:04.830
of technicality behind it that what
he is playing, what I'm playing,

01:10:04.830 --> 01:10:07.190
we're constantly bounding
off each other.

01:10:07.190 --> 01:10:14.110 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Yeah, because I
mean, if you're looking at the tabla

01:10:14.110 --> 01:10:17.650
in terms of sort of a western drum,
there's no clear, you know, beat,

01:10:17.650 --> 01:10:21.410
structure that somebody who's used
to listening to just a regular--

01:10:21.410 --> 01:10:22.710
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yeah.

01:10:22.710 --> 01:10:24.010
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: -- western
drum can actually pick up.

01:10:24.010 --> 01:10:25.310
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Because
western drums are very structured.

01:10:25.310 --> 01:10:26.610
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Yeah.

01:10:26.610 --> 01:10:28.320
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: And
there is no language to it.

01:10:28.320 --> 01:10:32.590
So, you just pretty much
going by them, the sound--

01:10:32.590 --> 01:10:34.440
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Of
the bass drum, yeah.

01:10:34.440 --> 01:10:36.910
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: --
of the bass and so on.

01:10:36.910 --> 01:10:41.760
But if I throw you off
to a different intro

01:10:41.760 --> 01:10:45.550
of style then you cannot
come back to that one.

01:10:45.550 --> 01:10:49.020
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: So, could
you play a 16 beat sample?

01:10:49.020 --> 01:10:50.320
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Sure

01:10:50.320 --> 01:10:53.480
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: -- and name
the beats as you're going.

01:10:53.480 --> 01:10:54.780
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Right, right.

01:10:54.780 --> 01:10:56.080
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: First, second--

01:10:56.080 --> 01:10:57.380
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: So first,
I'm going to describe it

01:10:57.380 --> 01:10:58.680
as one, two, three, four.

01:10:58.680 --> 01:11:04.400
So, the 16 beats is going like one,
two, three, four, two, two, three,

01:11:04.400 --> 01:11:08.590
four, three, three, three,
four, four, four, two, four.

01:11:08.590 --> 01:11:11.510
OK. So, or we can say--

01:11:11.510 --> 01:11:17.120
[ Humming and Drum Beating ]

01:11:17.120 --> 01:11:22.050
-- this is the language that
replaced one, two, three, four.

01:11:22.050 --> 01:11:23.350
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Right.

01:11:23.350 --> 01:11:24.650
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: OK?

01:11:24.650 --> 01:11:28.690
Now, once you established this
rhythmic structure then you can do

01:11:28.690 --> 01:11:32.310
just about anything and there are
like thousands of compositions

01:11:32.310 --> 01:11:34.210
to travel around that cycle.

01:11:34.210 --> 01:11:35.510
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: OK.

01:11:35.510 --> 01:11:36.810
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: OK.

01:11:36.810 --> 01:11:40.550
So, for example, I'm just giving
you the beat and then moving

01:11:40.550 --> 01:11:43.510
around to do the different
things, so.

01:11:43.510 --> 01:11:49.510
[ Counting and Drum Beating ]

01:11:49.510 --> 01:12:08.510
[ Humming and Drum Beating ]

01:12:08.510 --> 01:12:16.510
[ Music ]

01:12:16.510 --> 01:12:46.370
[ Humming and Drum Beating ]

01:12:46.370 --> 01:12:48.170
&gt;&gt; [Background Music]
Soumya Chakraverty:

01:12:48.170 --> 01:12:51.420
And you should talk
about what a tihai is.

01:12:51.420 --> 01:12:54.740
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: A tihai is
something that repeats three times.

01:12:54.740 --> 01:12:56.040
Tihai, three.

01:12:56.040 --> 01:12:57.340
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Yeah.

01:12:57.340 --> 01:12:58.640
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: And something,

01:12:58.640 --> 01:12:59.940
it could be a syllable
repeating three times,

01:12:59.940 --> 01:13:02.020
it could be a composition
repeating three times

01:13:02.020 --> 01:13:07.590
or it could be just a set
pattern repeating three times.

01:13:07.590 --> 01:13:10.050
For example, there's a
pattern called [inaudible].

01:13:10.050 --> 01:13:12.090
[ Humming and Drum Beating ]

01:13:12.090 --> 01:13:13.390
Is a tihai.

01:13:13.390 --> 01:13:16.870
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: And you
can play that with any--

01:13:16.870 --> 01:13:19.330
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: You can
insert that in anywhere.

01:13:19.330 --> 01:13:20.630 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Any rhythmic cycle?

01:13:20.630 --> 01:13:21.930
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: In a
composition, rhythmic cycle.

01:13:21.930 --> 01:13:23.230
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: OK.

01:13:23.230 --> 01:13:24.530
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: As long as
it's hitting the first beat.

01:13:24.530 --> 01:13:27.380
So, you-- You're inserting
a repetition

01:13:27.380 --> 01:13:31.940
of three whether it's the entire
composition or whether it's--

01:13:31.940 --> 01:13:37.420
I'll show you the example of just
tihai applied in different areas.

01:13:37.420 --> 01:13:41.510
For example, just a syllable
repeating three times.

01:13:41.510 --> 01:13:51.240
[ Humming and Drum Beating ]

01:13:51.240 --> 01:13:58.510
I'm repeating a particular
phrase three times.

01:13:58.510 --> 01:14:09.100
[ Humming and Drum Beating ]

01:14:09.100 --> 01:14:12.580
So, phrase repeating three times.

01:14:12.580 --> 01:14:16.720
Now, the entire composition
repeating three times.

01:14:16.720 --> 01:14:20.870
There's a small composition for the
beginners level wherein they learn.

01:14:20.870 --> 01:14:23.600
It's called-- It starts
with kut [phonetic].

01:14:23.600 --> 01:14:25.510
This phrase is called kut.

01:14:25.510 --> 01:14:37.090
[ Humming and Drum Beating ]

01:14:37.090 --> 01:14:41.450
The entire phrase repeated
three times.

01:14:41.450 --> 01:14:43.550
And you can play it
in different speed

01:14:43.550 --> 01:14:48.420
and the way we keep speed
is by clapping our signs.

01:14:48.420 --> 01:14:51.610
And the word in our language,

01:14:51.610 --> 01:14:54.560
the word rhythmic pattern
is called taal.

01:14:54.560 --> 01:14:55.860
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Right.

01:14:55.860 --> 01:14:57.910
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: And
taal came from clapping.

01:14:57.910 --> 01:14:59.210
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: All right.

01:14:59.210 --> 01:15:00.510
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak:
It's called taal.

01:15:00.510 --> 01:15:04.490
So the-- Where we keep the speed,
one, two, three, four, five, six,

01:15:04.490 --> 01:15:09.950
seven, eight, nine, 10, 11, 12,
13, 14, 15, 16, and one, OK?

01:15:09.950 --> 01:15:12.290
One, two, three, four, five,
six, seven, keeping the taal

01:15:12.290 --> 01:15:17.140
in the same speed, or saying
it in different times.

01:15:17.140 --> 01:15:23.760 position:56%
So, that also has a different effect
and preparing the tihai on the spot

01:15:23.760 --> 01:15:26.370
for it to match that one
is something that you--

01:15:26.370 --> 01:15:27.670
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: You have to--

01:15:27.670 --> 01:15:30.570
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: --
make, sort of workout.

01:15:30.570 --> 01:15:32.790
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Because the
one is the beat that is--

01:15:32.790 --> 01:15:34.090
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yes.

01:15:34.090 --> 01:15:35.450
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: -- everybody hears
that, that's the beat you hear.

01:15:35.450 --> 01:15:37.740
You may know everything
else might just sort of--

01:15:37.740 --> 01:15:39.850
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: And the
compositions in instrumental

01:15:39.850 --> 01:15:46.030
or vocal music are also normally to
emphasize main note is that one--

01:15:46.030 --> 01:15:48.230
it's the starting point
of the beat cycle.

01:15:48.230 --> 01:15:51.890
Now, the composition may not
begin from the one but you--

01:15:51.890 --> 01:15:57.010 position:56%
it's always the main emphasis note
and that's where the instrumentalist

01:15:57.010 --> 01:16:00.310
and the percussionist
hand off each other.

01:16:00.310 --> 01:16:03.740
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: So that's--
that occurs throughout the--

01:16:03.740 --> 01:16:05.040
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Throughout.

01:16:05.040 --> 01:16:06.340
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: --
throughout the composition.

01:16:06.340 --> 01:16:07.640
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Yeah.

01:16:07.640 --> 01:16:09.020
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: It's not
just the beginning where the--

01:16:09.020 --> 01:16:13.390
that note is emphasized
but throughout.

01:16:13.390 --> 01:16:14.690
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Yeah.

01:16:14.690 --> 01:16:16.650
So, you may have something
that starts from the--

01:16:16.650 --> 01:16:19.500
maybe the ninth note
or the 12th note.

01:16:19.500 --> 01:16:21.230
But the composition
may start from there,

01:16:21.230 --> 01:16:25.260
but the main note it
will always hit is the--

01:16:25.260 --> 01:16:27.710
and I'm going to start
to demonstrate

01:16:27.710 --> 01:16:32.030
that by playing something
so that you can see that.

01:16:32.030 --> 01:16:36.790
So this composition that I'm
going to play in a different raag,

01:16:36.790 --> 01:16:39.760
it starts from-- and I'm
going to give it away

01:16:39.760 --> 01:16:41.470 position:56%
and it starts from the seventh beat.

01:16:41.470 --> 01:16:46.810
But you can see that the emphasis
of the composition is going

01:16:46.810 --> 01:16:49.510
to be on that first beat.

01:16:49.510 --> 01:17:37.170
[ Music ]

01:17:37.170 --> 01:17:43.670
So, you could see that in
this case, that emphasize

01:17:43.670 --> 01:17:48.640
of that composition was at [music]
that kind of that slow drawn

01:17:48.640 --> 01:17:53.490
out melody but that was the
highlight of that whole--

01:17:53.490 --> 01:17:55.650
the entire composition
and he knows that.

01:17:55.650 --> 01:17:58.510
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: To him,
but to me, the marking point--

01:17:58.510 --> 01:18:01.040
[ Humming ]

01:18:01.040 --> 01:18:02.340
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: That's it.

01:18:02.340 --> 01:18:03.640
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak:
Now, that's the--

01:18:03.640 --> 01:18:05.030
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty:
That's the landing point.

01:18:05.030 --> 01:18:06.640
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: That's
my landing point and that's

01:18:06.640 --> 01:18:09.350
where the thing is starting.

01:18:09.350 --> 01:18:14.180
So, to us, music is
talking to us differently.

01:18:14.180 --> 01:18:15.480
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Yeah.

01:18:15.480 --> 01:18:18.210
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: From-- To me,
it's the tabla player's language,

01:18:18.210 --> 01:18:23.080
for him it's the melodic language
but the appeal is the same.

01:18:23.080 --> 01:18:24.380
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: And
you're syncing both.

01:18:24.380 --> 01:18:27.690
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: And
we are syncing those two.

01:18:27.690 --> 01:18:28.990
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Yeah.

01:18:28.990 --> 01:18:31.930
Just-- So, how are
we doing for time?

01:18:31.930 --> 01:18:35.050
&gt;&gt; We're fine, it's
about five to four.

01:18:35.050 --> 01:18:39.070
So, it-- are there other things
that you want to talk about

01:18:39.070 --> 01:18:40.380
or cover, I mean, it's very--

01:18:40.380 --> 01:18:41.970
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: I mean,
we can talk forever.

01:18:41.970 --> 01:18:43.270
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty:
That's the point.

01:18:43.270 --> 01:18:44.610
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: And there's
so many things to talk about.

01:18:44.610 --> 01:18:47.120
&gt;&gt; Thirty-four minutes left.

01:18:47.120 --> 01:18:51.310
&gt;&gt; Left. And [inaudible].

01:18:51.310 --> 01:18:54.710
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: We got
30 something minutes.

01:18:54.710 --> 01:18:57.320
&gt;&gt; You have that if
you like to use it.

01:18:57.320 --> 01:19:00.530
Come on make some gimmick?

01:19:00.530 --> 01:19:01.830
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Yeah.

01:19:01.830 --> 01:19:06.320
And, you know, what we could do
is demonstrate a few different

01:19:06.320 --> 01:19:07.620
rhythmic cycles.

01:19:07.620 --> 01:19:08.920
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yeah.

01:19:08.920 --> 01:19:10.220
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Well,
that would be great.

01:19:10.220 --> 01:19:12.190
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: And
also, the fact that, you know,

01:19:12.190 --> 01:19:16.910
I think I made this point during
the concert of how we can start

01:19:16.910 --> 01:19:21.390
from a very slow tempo and then
it builds up to the, you know,

01:19:21.390 --> 01:19:24.510
the very fast tempo and
you can go on there.

01:19:24.510 --> 01:19:28.120
So, there's so many different
rhythmic patterns we talked about.

01:19:28.120 --> 01:19:29.420
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yeah.

01:19:29.420 --> 01:19:32.130
There was 100 to 165 taals.

01:19:32.130 --> 01:19:34.170
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: So, this
one question I have though

01:19:34.170 --> 01:19:37.150
about rhythmic pattern
and maybe especially,

01:19:37.150 --> 01:19:39.420
I think, in the 16 beats.

01:19:39.420 --> 01:19:41.530
They talked about the
empty beat, the khali?

01:19:41.530 --> 01:19:42.830
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yes.

01:19:42.830 --> 01:19:44.130
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Yes.

01:19:44.130 --> 01:19:45.430
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: So, is that-- can
you talk a little bit about that?

01:19:45.430 --> 01:19:46.730
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Sure.

01:19:46.730 --> 01:19:48.030
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: And see if
that is in the other beats

01:19:48.030 --> 01:19:49.330
that you're going to talk about.

01:19:49.330 --> 01:19:50.630
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Yeah.

01:19:50.630 --> 01:19:52.100 position:56%
And you should talked about not only
in 16 beat but talk about rupak tal.

01:19:52.100 --> 01:19:53.400
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yeah.

01:19:53.400 --> 01:19:54.700
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty:
Because it starts from a khali.

01:19:54.700 --> 01:19:56.000
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yeah.

01:19:56.000 --> 01:19:57.300
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: OK.

01:19:57.300 --> 01:19:58.600
So, introduce the concept of khali.

01:19:58.600 --> 01:19:59.900
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yeah.

01:19:59.900 --> 01:20:03.780
So the concept of khali or
emptiness are no-clap, so to speak.

01:20:03.780 --> 01:20:06.790
So, the way the 16 beats--

01:20:06.790 --> 01:20:09.170
and one of the reasons it's
called the mother of all taals

01:20:09.170 --> 01:20:13.590
because this is the first thing
we learn when we start tabla.

01:20:13.590 --> 01:20:14.890
Why do we learn that?

01:20:14.890 --> 01:20:18.380
Because within 16 beats,
all the other taals,

01:20:18.380 --> 01:20:22.220
all the other major
taals are hidden.

01:20:22.220 --> 01:20:26.770
So, it's sort of like a clue
to learn other taals also.

01:20:26.770 --> 01:20:29.860
And that's where the
tali-khali concept comes.

01:20:29.860 --> 01:20:34.110
And the way the-- the way
we keep tali-khali or clap

01:20:34.110 --> 01:20:40.770
or no-clap is the very
first beat is clapped

01:20:40.770 --> 01:20:45.540
and the fifth beat is clapped and
then the ninth beat is not clapped.

01:20:45.540 --> 01:20:51.460
And then the 12the, 13th beat
is not-- is clapped again.

01:20:51.460 --> 01:20:58.310 position:56%
So, the way we keep count of that
is one, two, three, four, five, six,

01:20:58.310 --> 01:21:05.890
seven, eight, nine, 10, 11,
12, 13, 14, 15, 16 and one.

01:21:05.890 --> 01:21:07.190
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Right.

01:21:07.190 --> 01:21:08.990
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: So, if
I use the tabla language,

01:21:08.990 --> 01:21:18.310
[ Humming ]

01:21:18.310 --> 01:21:24.590
Now, this is my formula
of the 16 beats.

01:21:24.590 --> 01:21:32.450 position:56%
And I want to demonstrate to you how
the other taals are hidden in it.

01:21:32.450 --> 01:21:37.290
So, But you were keeping
the 16 beat alive,

01:21:37.290 --> 01:21:42.790
now you're saying kaherava,
which is four beats.

01:21:42.790 --> 01:21:44.590
So--

01:21:44.590 --> 01:21:56.210
[ Humming ]

01:21:56.210 --> 01:21:59.510
Sorry. This is six beats.

01:21:59.510 --> 01:22:08.060
[ Humming ]

01:22:08.060 --> 01:22:09.360
There.

01:22:09.360 --> 01:22:11.320
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: So the
ninth is always dropped.

01:22:11.320 --> 01:22:12.620
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Yeah.

01:22:12.620 --> 01:22:13.920
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yeah.

01:22:13.920 --> 01:22:15.220
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Wherever it goes.

01:22:15.220 --> 01:22:16.520
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yes.

01:22:16.520 --> 01:22:20.510
And the same way, if I'm
saying kaherava, which is four.

01:22:20.510 --> 01:22:29.760
[ Humming ]

01:22:29.760 --> 01:22:36.740
So, kaherava and then, you know,
there are rupak tal, seven beats,

01:22:36.740 --> 01:22:39.320
nine beats and it gets
more and more complicated.

01:22:39.320 --> 01:22:41.840
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: But one
thing I'd like to clarify just to--

01:22:41.840 --> 01:22:47.470
you feel-- I mean, he showed that
those other beat cycles can exist

01:22:47.470 --> 01:22:49.510
within the 16 strike-- cycle.

01:22:49.510 --> 01:22:52.350
But if you just want to recite

01:22:52.350 --> 01:22:56.770
like he recited dadra,
which is six beats.

01:22:56.770 --> 01:23:00.270
And then, you want to show
that same counting, it's one,

01:23:00.270 --> 01:23:02.640
two, three, four, five, six.

01:23:02.640 --> 01:23:06.300
So, the same clap and
blank technique comes

01:23:06.300 --> 01:23:07.670
into other forms as well.

01:23:07.670 --> 01:23:09.330
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Oh, into
other beat cycles as well.

01:23:09.330 --> 01:23:11.150
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yes,
because if they're your major--

01:23:11.150 --> 01:23:14.910
the reason why I didn't
go into that is

01:23:14.910 --> 01:23:20.100
because here are my--
tintal is my major.

01:23:20.100 --> 01:23:22.940
The other is being played as minor.

01:23:22.940 --> 01:23:28.340
But if I make-- let's say, dadra as
major and then tintal within the--

01:23:28.340 --> 01:23:29.640
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty:
So, you're overlaying.

01:23:29.640 --> 01:23:30.940
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak:
You're overlaying it.

01:23:30.940 --> 01:23:32.240
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: OK.

01:23:32.240 --> 01:23:34.110
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: And that's
where it gets complicated.

01:23:34.110 --> 01:23:35.410
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Yeah.

01:23:35.410 --> 01:23:38.540
But, you know, interestingly
not every beat cycle starts

01:23:38.540 --> 01:23:39.840
from the claps.

01:23:39.840 --> 01:23:41.800
So, I was asking him about rupak.

01:23:41.800 --> 01:23:44.660
Rupak is a seven beat cycle.

01:23:44.660 --> 01:23:45.960
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yeah.

01:23:45.960 --> 01:23:47.260
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: It's--

01:23:47.260 --> 01:23:48.560
[ Humming ]

01:23:48.560 --> 01:23:50.360
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak:
So it goes like--

01:23:50.360 --> 01:23:56.040
[ Humming ]

01:23:56.040 --> 01:23:57.340
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Yeah, so--

01:23:57.340 --> 01:23:59.430
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: So how
does that work out on--

01:23:59.430 --> 01:24:04.110
so, when you're playing the
tabla, your fingers do not touch.

01:24:04.110 --> 01:24:05.410
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: No,
but internally, we're--

01:24:05.410 --> 01:24:06.770
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: You're
not making any--

01:24:06.770 --> 01:24:08.070
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty:
It's a softer note.

01:24:08.070 --> 01:24:09.370
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: It's a soft--

01:24:09.370 --> 01:24:13.030 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: We have din,
means-- I mean, also, in the tintal,

01:24:13.030 --> 01:24:16.200
when he is playing the
khali, it's a softer note.

01:24:16.200 --> 01:24:17.500
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: OK.

01:24:17.500 --> 01:24:18.800
It's not a--

01:24:18.800 --> 01:24:20.100
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty:
It's not a heavy note.

01:24:20.100 --> 01:24:21.400
And more often, he's
not playing the dayan,

01:24:21.400 --> 01:24:23.580
he's just making a
tonic sound with dayan.

01:24:23.580 --> 01:24:24.880
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: With the dayan.

01:24:24.880 --> 01:24:26.680
So, it's going like--

01:24:26.680 --> 01:24:34.150
[ Music ]

01:24:34.150 --> 01:24:35.800
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: [Background
Music] Was that the khali?

01:24:35.800 --> 01:24:37.600
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Yeah.

01:24:37.600 --> 01:24:44.460
[ Humming and Drum Beating ]

01:24:44.460 --> 01:24:47.400
So you can hear the softer note.

01:24:47.400 --> 01:24:52.990
As a audience, you can always
see where the tali-khali is and,

01:24:52.990 --> 01:24:56.280
you know, listening if you know
the music then you appreciate that.

01:24:56.280 --> 01:25:00.460
But the idea of the tali-kali
came from where there is emphasis

01:25:00.460 --> 01:25:04.520
on certain beats and whether
it's softer or draw back on--

01:25:04.520 --> 01:25:05.820
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Right.

01:25:05.820 --> 01:25:07.120 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: -- obviously.

01:25:07.120 --> 01:25:09.750
you still have to keep the beat
but, you know, since you mentioned,

01:25:09.750 --> 01:25:14.730
there is also-- there
are certain beat cycles

01:25:14.730 --> 01:25:17.160
where there is a blank
note, truly a blank note.

01:25:17.160 --> 01:25:23.180 position:56%
For example, there's a taal pattern
called dhamar, it's a 14 beat cycle.

01:25:23.180 --> 01:25:28.000
The legend goes that it came-- it
was drawn from an elephant's walk.

01:25:28.000 --> 01:25:29.830
Now, so, why don't
you recite dhamar?

01:25:29.830 --> 01:25:31.130
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yeah.

