So, the dhamar tal is 14.

01:25:33.030 --> 01:25:35.510
It goes like--

01:25:35.510 --> 01:25:46.060
[ Humming ]

01:25:46.060 --> 01:25:48.710
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: So, you--
there are two blanks in there.

01:25:48.710 --> 01:25:50.010
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Right.

01:25:50.010 --> 01:25:51.810
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty:
He recited the--

01:25:51.810 --> 01:25:54.740
[ Humming ]

01:25:54.740 --> 01:25:56.540
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: So how is that--

01:25:56.540 --> 01:25:59.750
[ Humming ]

01:25:59.750 --> 01:26:03.840
And how does that work out on the--

01:26:03.840 --> 01:26:05.140
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: On this?

01:26:05.140 --> 01:26:06.440
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: -- tabla?

01:26:06.440 --> 01:26:07.740
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Yeah.

01:26:07.740 --> 01:26:09.040
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: It's
actually came from [inaudible].

01:26:09.040 --> 01:26:10.340
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: OK that one.

01:26:10.340 --> 01:26:11.640
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: So, this
particular taal used to be,

01:26:11.640 --> 01:26:14.660
still is, sung with dhrupad, but
a lot of the instrumentalist--

01:26:14.660 --> 01:26:16.160
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Let
him play and then I'm--

01:26:16.160 --> 01:26:17.880
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: And
then he will do the melody.

01:26:17.880 --> 01:26:20.280
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: A melody
