01:26:40.910 --> 01:26:42.210
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Yeah.

01:26:42.210 --> 01:26:43.510
Just like this kind
of poddling elephant.

01:26:43.510 --> 01:26:49.140
And the idea is that because
of those two blank notes

01:26:49.140 --> 01:26:54.580 position:56%
or blank rhythms, it can throw the
instrumentalist or the vocalist off.

01:26:54.580 --> 01:26:55.960
So, this is the--

01:26:55.960 --> 01:26:57.260
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Their revenge.

01:26:57.260 --> 01:27:00.320
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: -- revenge
on [inaudible] revenge on that.

01:27:00.320 --> 01:27:07.580
So, I'm going to play a little
composition set to raag kedar

01:27:07.580 --> 01:27:14.160
and this was composed by
my teacher's contemporary,

01:27:14.160 --> 01:27:19.360
a very famous musician
Pandit Budhadev Dasgupta.

01:27:19.360 --> 01:27:25.060 position:56%
And this, again, this starts from
the eighth beat but we can again see

01:27:25.060 --> 01:27:31.370
where the emphasis
of the melody points

01:27:31.370 --> 01:27:34.510
to that sound or the starting beat.

01:27:34.510 --> 01:29:58.040
[ Music ]

01:29:58.040 --> 01:29:59.340
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Perfect.

01:29:59.340 --> 01:30:01.910
Very different from--

01:30:01.910 --> 01:30:06.130
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Very
different, very different.

01:30:06.130 --> 01:30:07.430
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty:
No, but this is--

01:30:07.430 --> 01:30:11.050
this actually gave you a
flavor of the ancient tradition

01:30:11.050 --> 01:30:14.140
that they will talk about
which is the dhrupad style.

01:30:14.140 --> 01:30:15.440
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: OK.

01:30:15.440 --> 01:30:17.740
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: And
there's a vocal aspect of this type

01:30:17.740 --> 01:30:23.800
of composition that evolved
into modern day singing.

01:30:23.800 --> 01:30:27.040
But these are very, very
traditional and the composition

01:30:27.040 --> 01:30:29.400
that I played is not
very old, obviously,--

01:30:29.400 --> 01:30:30.700
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Right.

01:30:30.700 --> 01:30:32.000
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: --

01:30:32.000 --> 01:30:33.300
it was made in probably
last 15, 20 years ago.

01:30:33.300 --> 01:30:37.100 position:56%
But the fact is that that
composition reflects the traditional

01:30:37.100 --> 01:30:40.230
style of the dhrupad.

01:30:40.230 --> 01:30:46.550
And dhamar is a taal cycle that
was very extensively use in dhrupad

01:30:46.550 --> 01:30:51.010
as long-- as well as with another
12 beat cycle called cautal.

01:30:51.010 --> 01:30:52.310
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: And
is dhrupad slower?

01:30:52.310 --> 01:30:53.750
Is it more-- I mean, what is it?

01:30:53.750 --> 01:30:55.050
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak:
It's more meditative.

01:30:55.050 --> 01:30:56.350
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: It's
more meditative.

01:30:56.350 --> 01:30:57.650
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty:
It's more meditative.

01:30:57.650 --> 01:31:02.230
Actually dhrupad has a
very big component of alap.

01:31:02.230 --> 01:31:03.530
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: OK.

01:31:03.530 --> 01:31:06.110 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: And even
before the percussion start playing,

01:31:06.110 --> 01:31:11.020 position:56%
there was almost like an hour to two
hours sometimes of just the vocalist

01:31:11.020 --> 01:31:12.950 position:56%
or the instrument just playing alap.

01:31:12.950 --> 01:31:17.240
And the alap section, you had
asked me earlier, I did not answer.

01:31:17.240 --> 01:31:20.760
There is a component of the
alap section, which is--

01:31:20.760 --> 01:31:23.320
there are actually
four stages of an alap.

01:31:23.320 --> 01:31:25.930
At least, in sarod vocabulary.

01:31:25.930 --> 01:31:31.270
So there, the first phase which
is the most commonly heard,

01:31:31.270 --> 01:31:34.710 position:56%
which is without any kind of rhythm,

01:31:34.710 --> 01:31:37.440
just purely the bars
being introduced

01:31:37.440 --> 01:31:40.450
and as far as being introduced.

01:31:40.450 --> 01:31:44.460
Then comes a part which
where there is a rhythm part

01:31:44.460 --> 01:31:46.290
to it and it's called jhur.

01:31:46.290 --> 01:31:50.120
And this also came from the
dhrupad, the vocals music.

01:31:50.120 --> 01:31:57.790
Then, you start to, you know, use
some of that aspect of the rhythm,

01:31:57.790 --> 01:32:00.620
it's not set to the beat
cycle but, you know,

01:32:00.620 --> 01:32:04.130
you can hear that there's
a rhythm part to it.

01:32:04.130 --> 01:32:07.380
Or no, a mellow-- a
rhythmic aspect of it.

01:32:07.380 --> 01:32:08.680
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: To
the melody of it?

01:32:08.680 --> 01:32:09.980
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty:
To the melody.

01:32:09.980 --> 01:32:11.280
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: OK.

01:32:11.280 --> 01:32:12.580
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty:
And, I'm going to play

01:32:12.580 --> 01:32:14.020
in a few seconds to
show or demonstrate.

01:32:14.020 --> 01:32:18.290 position:56%
And then, it goes into, you know,
full embellishments like [inaudible]

01:32:18.290 --> 01:32:22.310
like you do the, you know,

01:32:22.310 --> 01:32:26.230
rhythm except that it's
still at 20 beat cycle.

01:32:26.230 --> 01:32:28.670
And then finally the
very fast portion

01:32:28.670 --> 01:32:31.570
of the jhala, that's also played.

01:32:31.570 --> 01:32:37.110 position:56%
So, I'm just going to again, play a
little bit of alap in the same round

01:32:37.110 --> 01:32:39.510
that I was playing kedar.

01:32:39.510 --> 01:33:32.040
[ Music ]

01:33:32.040 --> 01:33:38.180
So, I mean, I played a very
brief alap, but you could--

01:33:38.180 --> 01:33:43.560
you could see how this could be
elaborated to a significant extent.

01:33:43.560 --> 01:33:44.860
Then comes the jor portion.

01:33:44.860 --> 01:33:46.160
How does that work?

01:33:46.160 --> 01:33:47.960
It starts again very slowly.

01:33:47.960 --> 01:34:44.040
[ Music ]

01:34:44.040 --> 01:34:45.440
And so it goes.

01:34:45.440 --> 01:34:48.330
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: And so
that has a greater beat.

01:34:48.330 --> 01:34:49.660
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: So
I'm actually keeping the beat

01:34:49.660 --> 01:34:56.210
or the tempo more to
say not olny beat.

01:34:56.210 --> 01:34:59.010
The tempo through,
until that's come.

01:34:59.010 --> 01:35:00.310
[ Music ]

01:35:00.310 --> 01:35:03.130
And this would pick
up as I'm going along.

01:35:03.130 --> 01:35:07.510
And when it-- what's--
gets to a point that.

01:35:07.510 --> 01:35:57.060
[ Music ]

01:35:57.060 --> 01:36:02.470
So, you can see that
there's a lot of [inaudible]

01:36:02.470 --> 01:36:06.740 position:56%
that is being [inaudible] but
again, I'm just keeping my own beat.

01:36:06.740 --> 01:36:08.070
Not just [inaudible].

01:36:08.070 --> 01:36:09.370
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yes.

01:36:09.370 --> 01:36:10.670
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: This
is the third phase of alap,

01:36:10.670 --> 01:36:14.510
the fourth phase actually
goes into fourth scales alap.

01:36:14.510 --> 01:37:10.040
[ Music ]

01:37:10.040 --> 01:37:14.680
And finally, there
would be a-- so this--

01:37:14.680 --> 01:37:20.050
this whole tradition that is now
played today in instrumental music,

01:37:20.050 --> 01:37:25.530
actually came from
dhrupad, so they do this

01:37:25.530 --> 01:37:28.590
through vocalization techniques.

01:37:28.590 --> 01:37:29.890
And they would recite both.

01:37:29.890 --> 01:37:31.190
And so, what I'm playing as
[humming], they would say--

01:37:31.190 --> 01:37:32.490
[ Humming ]

01:37:32.490 --> 01:37:38.730
And then later on, this
actually walk into another form

01:37:38.730 --> 01:37:42.920
of singing called perana, which is
also taken from instrumental music,

01:37:42.920 --> 01:37:47.430
went back to local
music and was molded

01:37:47.430 --> 01:37:50.250 position:56%
after and-- molded after percussion.

01:37:50.250 --> 01:37:54.890
So, dhrupad has given
a lot to-- back to--

01:37:54.890 --> 01:38:00.510
or it has given a lot of ideas that
have branched into different forms

01:38:00.510 --> 01:38:02.760
of vocal and instrumental music.

01:38:02.760 --> 01:38:04.060
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yes.

01:38:04.060 --> 01:38:05.360
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: It's fantastic.

01:38:05.360 --> 01:38:07.310
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: And
the same thing with tabla,

01:38:07.310 --> 01:38:09.900
when they are like-- the
whole concept of alap,

01:38:09.900 --> 01:38:13.180
I raised it when I was
saying that when you--

01:38:13.180 --> 01:38:20.480
when a tabla soloist is playing
table, he starts off with peshkar.

01:38:20.480 --> 01:38:23.800
And peshkar is the alap of tabla.

01:38:23.800 --> 01:38:29.290
If, for example, he played
that four stages of alap,

01:38:29.290 --> 01:38:37.010
we also do the same thing when
we play solo and that happens

01:38:37.010 --> 01:38:40.760
in the peshkar style when
we perform and the peshkar--

01:38:40.760 --> 01:38:42.900
and the first part
of the peshkar is,

01:38:42.900 --> 01:38:46.550
it sticks to the school
that it comes from.

01:38:46.550 --> 01:38:50.510
For example Delhi peshkar
uses more finger techniques

01:38:50.510 --> 01:38:52.390
of these two fingers.

01:38:52.390 --> 01:38:58.720
Farrukhabad and Lucknow, which
I like a lot, deals with a lot

01:38:58.720 --> 01:39:01.030
of meditative type syllables.

01:39:01.030 --> 01:39:02.830
For example--

01:39:02.830 --> 01:39:07.360
[ Foreign Language ]

01:39:07.360 --> 01:39:11.830
And all these syllables are
coming from the Lucknow style.

01:39:11.830 --> 01:39:13.130
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: And
does it-- is it.

01:39:13.130 --> 01:39:14.430
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: And--

01:39:14.430 --> 01:39:15.730
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Does
it go from slow to fast?

01:39:15.730 --> 01:39:17.030
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: It's very slow.

01:39:17.030 --> 01:39:18.330
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: As well.

01:39:18.330 --> 01:39:19.630
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yeah.

01:39:19.630 --> 01:39:20.930
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty:
You want to play some?

01:39:20.930 --> 01:39:23.700
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: It's very slow
and it's set to a very slow tintal

01:39:23.700 --> 01:39:27.700
or any taal for example, I mean,
peshkar could be in any taal.

01:39:27.700 --> 01:39:31.380
But I can show you
a little bit of --

01:39:31.380 --> 01:39:32.680
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty:
I'll keep the--

01:39:32.680 --> 01:39:38.510 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Peshkar
demonstration and this-- the tintal.

01:39:38.510 --> 01:41:42.200
[ Music ]

01:41:42.200 --> 01:41:50.240
So, that's an example of
meditative slow style peshkar.

01:41:50.240 --> 01:41:55.830
I'll show you a mid part of
it, a little bit faster tempo.

01:41:55.830 --> 01:42:01.570
Not in the-- And our
bass tempo is the same.

01:42:01.570 --> 01:42:07.870
But the peshkar in
mid tempo moved up.

01:42:07.870 --> 01:42:12.510
And will developing
on the same rhythm.

01:42:12.510 --> 01:42:38.480
[ Music ]

01:42:38.480 --> 01:42:44.680 position:56%
So, this is-- This movement will be
developed into other rhythmic aspect

01:42:44.680 --> 01:42:48.880
of it, but it's going to go in same
bass tempo, but a different set.

01:42:48.880 --> 01:42:50.970
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty:
And, while he's doing--

01:42:50.970 --> 01:42:55.650
while they're doing the peshkar,
the instrumentalists or at least,

01:42:55.650 --> 01:42:59.660
I'm also trying to adapt
and play something similar.

01:42:59.660 --> 01:43:00.960
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yeah.

01:43:00.960 --> 01:43:02.260
&gt;&gt; Yeasmeen Khan: OK.

01:43:02.260 --> 01:43:03.560
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty:
That resembles the peshkar.

01:43:03.560 --> 01:43:04.860
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yeah.

01:43:04.860 --> 01:43:06.160
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: So, it's the
time where he's calling the shots.

01:43:06.160 --> 01:43:07.460
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Yeah.

01:43:07.460 --> 01:43:08.760
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak:
Yeah, just the reverse.

01:43:08.760 --> 01:43:10.060
Reversal of rules.

01:43:10.060 --> 01:43:13.510 position:56%
And then the third stages which is a
little bit faster just like he does.

01:43:13.510 --> 01:43:38.320
[ Music ]

01:43:38.320 --> 01:43:42.770
So, this is this the third stages,

01:43:42.770 --> 01:43:46.510
and the last stages
is the fourth stage.

01:43:46.510 --> 01:44:27.050
[ Music ]

01:44:27.050 --> 01:44:31.290
And we can develop this
also or in a bigger style,

01:44:31.290 --> 01:44:38.680 position:56%
but in order to develop this, you
need to play longer in a solo event.

01:44:38.680 --> 01:44:39.980
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: And, in-- OK.

01:44:39.980 --> 01:44:45.660
And in-- When you perform
together, say like in May, do you--

01:44:45.660 --> 01:44:49.140
in the middle of your performance--

01:44:49.140 --> 01:44:51.720
in the middle of the
performance do you--

01:44:51.720 --> 01:44:56.870
when the tabla player starts
to showcase his playing--

01:44:56.870 --> 01:44:58.170
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Absolutely.

01:44:58.170 --> 01:45:00.220
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan:-- do you
then go sort of recreate --

01:45:00.220 --> 01:45:01.520
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Lay low.

01:45:01.520 --> 01:45:02.820
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: --
lay low and sort of--

01:45:02.820 --> 01:45:04.120
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yeah, you.

01:45:04.120 --> 01:45:05.420
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: --
to a semi peshkar?

01:45:05.420 --> 01:45:06.720
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yeah.

01:45:06.720 --> 01:45:08.020
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Yeah.

01:45:08.020 --> 01:45:09.320
So, I'm actually repeating almost
playing over and over the same gat

01:45:09.320 --> 01:45:11.030
or the composition,
the fixed composition

01:45:11.030 --> 01:45:12.560
and that's just to keep going.

01:45:12.560 --> 01:45:13.860
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Yeah.

01:45:13.860 --> 01:45:15.160
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty:
Just like when he--

01:45:15.160 --> 01:45:16.460
when I'm playing, he's
keeping going,

01:45:16.460 --> 01:45:17.760
we do the reverse along the rolls.

01:45:17.760 --> 01:45:21.950
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: And is this
sort of a modern development?

01:45:21.950 --> 01:45:23.250
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty:
No, it's been there.

01:45:23.250 --> 01:45:24.550
That way forever.

01:45:24.550 --> 01:45:25.850
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak:
It's traditional.

01:45:25.850 --> 01:45:27.150
&gt;&gt; Soumya Chakraverty: Now, again,

01:45:27.150 --> 01:45:28.460
there has been some
healthy competition.

01:45:28.460 --> 01:45:34.480 position:56%
So there's a concept of [inaudible],
where you can both go and improvise

01:45:34.480 --> 01:45:37.780
without knowing where
each will say it,

01:45:37.780 --> 01:45:40.850
but in your head you
have the beat cycle,

01:45:40.850 --> 01:45:43.010
so you know where exactly
to come together.

01:45:43.010 --> 01:45:44.310
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: OK.

01:45:44.310 --> 01:45:45.610
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yeah.

01:45:45.610 --> 01:45:49.010 position:56%
And then, there's another thing, you
know, the reason why I said earlier,

01:45:49.010 --> 01:45:55.300
it's traditional, is because a
lot of schools for example there--

01:45:55.300 --> 01:46:01.040
for example Lucknow, if
you're playing a Lucknow badge

01:46:01.040 --> 01:46:04.640
or Lucknow style tabla
player, and you know that a lot

01:46:04.640 --> 01:46:09.080
of times the syllables
are harder, and it sound--

01:46:09.080 --> 01:46:11.300
it's got a ringing sound to it.

01:46:11.300 --> 01:46:14.670
Because they're used to
playing with dancing feet.

01:46:14.670 --> 01:46:18.020
And so, those-- the same tabla
players are going to play

01:46:18.020 --> 01:46:21.580
with instruments or vocal.

01:46:21.580 --> 01:46:23.750
In those cases, the vocalist

01:46:23.750 --> 01:46:26.030
or the instrumentalist
they just let them go.

01:46:26.030 --> 01:46:28.510
And they just play free flow.

01:46:28.510 --> 01:46:34.180
And you can see those
images coming in their hand.

01:46:34.180 --> 01:46:35.480
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: That's fantastic.

01:46:35.480 --> 01:46:36.780
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Yeah.

01:46:36.780 --> 01:46:38.380
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: Well, I think
we're coming to the end--

01:46:38.380 --> 01:46:39.680
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: OK.

01:46:39.680 --> 01:46:40.980
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: -- on tape.

01:46:40.980 --> 01:46:42.280
And I'd like to thank you both--

01:46:42.280 --> 01:46:43.580
&gt;&gt; Devapriya Nayak: Thank you.

01:46:43.580 --> 01:46:44.880
&gt;&gt; Yasmeen Khan: -- very much.

